name: Usman Qadir
review_text:
Enchanting experience that touched my soul during my recent visit to Kashmir. If you plan on exploring this breathtaking region, I highly recommend immersing yourself in the serene beauty of Dal Lake and indulging in the unforgettable experience of staying in a super deluxe houseboat.

Dal Lake is a mesmerizing gem that sparkles in the heart of Kashmir. As I embarked on my houseboat adventure, I was greeted by a surreal panorama of shimmering waters and majestic mountains, creating a picturesque backdrop that seemed straight out of a dream.

Staying in a houseboat on Dal Lake is an unparalleled delight. The luxurious super deluxe amenities provided surpassed all expectations, making me feel like royalty amidst the tranquil waters. The serene ambiance and the gentle sway of the houseboat lulled me into a state of pure relaxation and bliss.

One of the most memorable aspects of the experience was the floating shopping boats and the vibrant market that surrounds Dal Lake. It was an absolute delight to explore these floating wonders, browsing through a wide array of handicrafts, traditional artifacts, and local treasures. The cultural richness and artistic craftsmanship on display were awe-inspiring.

To enhance your Dal Lake experience, I urge you to indulge in a Shikara ride during the enchanting evening hours. Drifting through the calm waters, youll witness the golden hues of the setting sun reflecting upon the lakes surface, creating a magical ambiance that will leave you in awe. The tranquility of the surroundings and the gentle ripples of the water will transport you to a state of serenity and pure joy.

In conclusion, if youre planning a visit to Kashmir, I wholeheartedly recommend immersing yourself in the wonder of Dal Lake and the magical experience of staying in a super deluxe houseboat. Let the beauty of the lake and its surrounding floating market captivate your senses, while a serene Shikara ride adds the perfect touch of enchantment to your journey.

Embrace the allure of Kashmir and create cherished memories that will stay with you forever.

name: PRANAY LANDGE
review_text:
Breathtaking Beauty: Dal Lake in Srinagar is a truly mesmerizing destination with its picturesque surroundings, pristine waters, and stunning views of the surrounding mountains.

Tranquil Atmosphere: The lake offers a serene and peaceful ambiance, making it a perfect getaway from the bustling city life and an ideal spot for relaxation and rejuvenation.

Shikara Rides: Exploring the lake on a traditional Kashmiri wooden boat called a shikara is an enchanting experience. The leisurely rides allow you to soak in the captivating scenery and observe the floating gardens and houseboats.

Floating Market: The unique floating market on Dal Lake is a vibrant hub where local vendors sell a variety of handicrafts, jewelry, traditional clothing, and fresh produce, adding to the cultural charm of the place.

Houseboat Stays: Staying in a houseboat on Dal Lake is an unforgettable experience. The beautifully decorated houseboats offer comfortable accommodations and provide a glimpse into the rich Kashmiri culture and hospitality.

Water Sports and Activities: Dal Lake offers opportunities for adventure enthusiasts with various water sports like kayaking and canoeing. These activities add excitement and a dash of thrill to your visit.

Mughal Gardens: The lake is surrounded by stunning Mughal gardens, such as Shalimar Bagh and Nishat Bagh, which are adorned with vibrant flowers, fountains, and terraced landscapes, creating a visual delight.

Floating Gardens: The unique floating gardens, known as Rad in the local language, are an intriguing sight. These floating islands of vegetation, primarily made of decomposed organic matter, showcase the innovative agricultural practices of the locals.

Warm Hospitality: The locals in Srinagar are known for their warm and welcoming nature. Interacting with them and experiencing their hospitality adds a special touch to your visit to Dal Lake.

Photographic Paradise: For photography enthusiasts, Dal Lake presents endless opportunities to capture postcard-worthy shots, from the stunning reflections on the calm waters to the vibrant colors of the floating markets.

Dal Lake is a captivating and iconic feature of Kashmir, India. With its picturesque beauty, it is often referred to as the Jewel in the Crown of Kashmir. This serene lake spans over 15 square kilometers, surrounded by snow-capped mountains and lush greenery, creating a breathtaking landscape. The lake is dotted with vibrant houseboats, known as Shikaras, which offer leisurely rides and an opportunity to explore the floating markets and charming gardens. Dal Lake is not just a natural wonder but also a cultural hub, reflecting the unique way of life in the region.

Must take the shikara ride 200/head price may vary.

name: HAZIM MANZOOR
review_text:
Dal Lake in Srinagar, Kashmir, is a mesmerizing destination that offers a unique and enchanting experience. Surrounded by majestic mountains and lush greenery, the lake is often referred to as the jewel of Kashmir. I had the opportunity to visit Dal Lake recently, and it left an indelible mark on my memory.

One of the highlights of my Dal Lake experience was staying in a traditional houseboat called a shikara. These beautifully crafted boats are adorned with intricate woodwork and offer a comfortable and authentic way to immerse oneself in the lakes tranquility. As I glided across the pristine waters, I was captivated by the stunning reflections of the surrounding snow-capped peaks and vibrant gardens.

The floating markets on the lake were a sight to behold. Local vendors paddled their shikaras filled with a variety of goods, including fresh flowers, fruits, and handicrafts. I couldnt resist the temptation to buy some exquisite Kashmiri souvenirs as a reminder of this enchanting experience.

Exploring the lake by a shikara also allowed me to witness the unique way of life of the local people. I observed fishermen casting their nets and locals going about their daily routines along the waterways. The vibrant houseboats, with their colorful facades and intricately designed interiors, added to the charm of the surroundings.

A visit to the Mughal Gardens, such as the Shalimar Bagh and Nishat Bagh, which line the shores of Dal Lake, is a must. These meticulously manicured gardens, with their cascading fountains, blooming flowers, and terraced landscapes, offer a serene retreat and provide breathtaking views of the lake.

Another memorable aspect of my Dal Lake experience was witnessing the sunset over the mountains. The golden hues reflecting on the water and the tranquil ambiance created a truly magical moment. It was a time of reflection and appreciation for the natural beauty that surrounded me.

In conclusion, my experience at Dal Lake was nothing short of extraordinary. From the serene boat rides and vibrant floating markets to the stunning gardens and breathtaking sunsets, every moment spent at the lake was a feast for the senses. The beauty and tranquility of Dal Lake make it a must-visit destination for anyone seeking a unique and unforgettable experience in Kashmir.

name: raminder kaur
review_text:
Not recommended on a bad weather day.......
Dal lake has a great view. Spread over a vast area provides great spot for tourists but we did not have a good experience.
We took a shikara and weather started to deteriorate, and our shikara started to sink. There was no life jacket. Luckily our shikara driver managed to pull it towards a rescue boat. We had an infant with us as well. Somehow we were saved by CRPF resume boats. I wont recommend it on a rainy or bad weather day.
Otherwise the view is magnificent. There are beautiful spots to click pictures. Evening views are beautiful.

The water doesnt have a lot of depth. So life jackets are not provided. The water is dirty and polluted but the view is great at every turn.

review_text: Dal Lake in Srinagar, Kashmir, is a travelers paradise. Its serene ambiance and breathtaking natural beauty make it a must-visit destination. Staying in a traditional houseboat is a unique experience that immerses you in the lakes charm. Embarking on a tranquil Shikara ride allows you to explore the lakes hidden treasures and learn about its rich history. Dont miss the vibrant floating markets and gardens, where you can interact with locals and indulge in unique shopping experiences. The warm hospitality and picturesque views make Dal Lake an unforgettable destination for any traveler seeking peace and serenity amidst natures wonders.

review_text: Dal Lake is undoubtedly one of the top tourist destinations in Srinagar. Its breathtaking beauty and serene ambiance make it a prime attraction. name: Momin Naofil (StockTalkZone)
review_text:
Dal Lake in Kashmir is a breathtaking paradise that captivates the senses with its enchanting beauty and serene ambiance. The nature scenes surrounding the lake are simply mesmerizing, offering a picturesque backdrop of majestic mountains, lush greenery, and colorful flowers that create a truly magical setting.Speaking of houseboats, they are an integral part of the Dal Lake experience. These traditional, beautifully decorated boats offer a unique and unforgettable way to immerse oneself in the beauty of the lake. Staying in a houseboat allows you to wake up to the gentle ripples of the water and admire the elegant view of the lake right from your doorstep.The evening scenes at Dal Lake are truly captivating. As the sun sets behind the mountains, the entire area is bathed in a warm golden glow, creating a magical atmosphere. The shimmering reflections on the lakes surface and the silhouettes of the surrounding landscape paint a picture-perfect postcard scene. The tranquility of the evening is enhanced by the gentle lapping of water and the occasional sound of a boat passing by.
Visiting Dal Lake is an experience that rejuvenates the soul and leaves a lasting impression. The combination of natures beauty, the serene lake, the unique houseboat experience, and the enchanting evening scenes make it a must-visit destination for any nature lover or traveler seeking tranquility. Dal Lake is a true gem of Kashmir, offering a glimpse of paradise on Earth.

name: Varun Pai Kakode
review_text:
Went here on 30/04/23.

The Shikara ride at Dal lake has to be one of the most peaceful and calm experience I've ever done. There's not a sound except that of the water being paddled. If there is such a thing as inner peace, it could be found here.

Pick up is from one of the 28 odd gates to the lake. The Shikara first takes you to Nehru park. En-route you can have kahwa, and shop for some snacks or wooden items from the passing Shikaras.

At Nehru park you can click photos with traditional Kashmiri outfits, but decide on the prices and number/ delivery of photos beforehand. A speedboat ride is also available.

From there the Shikara goes through Meena bazaar the famous floating market of dal lake. You can buy handicrafts/ clothes here.

After that the ride ends back at the gates. Truly a great experience. Worthwhile spending more time or taking another ride also.

Tip- the shikara person will take you to a particular shop only, you can ask to be shown another shop if you find one pricey.
The prices of clothes/ shawls/ wooden items may be LESS in the Srinagar market compared to Dal lake (if you have time to explore it).

One of the best and prime tourist attractions in Srinagar. Dal lake offers extremely beautiful views. One can book a Houseboat and stay here. Shikara is your main source of transfer. You can visit floating vegetable gardens, shops and eat outs and the overall experience is awesome.
Wanna See the heaven while being alive?
You need to go for Kashmir Great Lakes Trek.
One of the most beautiful treks in India.
It validates Kashmirs mythical status as heaven on earth.
The Trail is super crowded with the lush green meadows, vista of colorful wild flowers and the pristine lakes made it up for it with a few boulder crossings.
The trek to the Kashmir Great Lakes Trek offers a lifetime experience of vintage memories that are so wonderfully tiring.
If you are travelling to Srinagar, riding on Shikara in Dal lake is must activity. It is a complete city living on water.

People started preparations for Winter. Winter is coming. Wow we experienced that.
There are farming lands, shops, ATMs, different vendors selling many things around. We visited Dal Lake in Oct-22. Experienced fall season(autumn) and there was a snow fall 2/3 days before.

We stayed there in HB Richards Green. Bang opposite to Gate No 5. Stay and food was good.

name: Shreesh Chaurasia
review_text:
I had an amazing experience at Dal Lake! The boating was definitely a highlight, with stunning views of the surrounding mountains and lush greenery. It was a relaxing and peaceful way to take in the beauty of the lake.

But what really made the experience special was the opportunity to have snacks on the boat itself. It was a unique and memorable experience, and added to the charm and relaxation of the boat ride.

In addition, the tour guide took us on a tour of the vegetable plantations on the lake, which was a fascinating and educational experience. It was incredible to see how the locals have adapted to living on the lake and how they have created a self-sustaining ecosystem.

Overall, I highly recommend a visit to Dal Lake for anyone traveling to Srinagar. The boat ride is a must-do, and the added experience of having snacks on the boat and seeing the vegetable plantations makes it even more special

name: Deepak Gupta
review_text:
The beauty of Dal Lake lies in its breathtaking scenery and tranquil surroundings. The lake is surrounded by snow-capped mountains, lush green forests, and colorful gardens, making it a picturesque location for photography and sightseeing.

Staying in a houseboat on Dal Lake is an experience like no other and is a must-do activity for anyone visiting the region.

Make Sure:
 Ensure that you book a houseboat situated in the midst of other houseboats, forming a U-shaped structure that creates the illusion of being in a floating city.

 Regarding the shikara ride, the usual charge is approximately Rs 500 for a duration of 45-60 minutes. Although the boatmen may initially demand exorbitant prices, negotiate with them and settle for a price ranging between Rs 500 to Rs 700.

name: STAND Together
review_text:
I recently had the pleasure of visiting Dal Lake in Srinagar, and I can confidently say that its one of the most beautiful places Ive ever seen. The lake is surrounded by stunning mountains and lush greenery, making for a breathtaking backdrop.

The lake itself is quite large and offers plenty of opportunities for activities such as shikara rides, water sports, and fishing. One of the highlights of my visit was taking a shikara ride, which is a traditional wooden boat that is unique to the region. It was a wonderful way to see the lake and take in the scenery.

The lake is also home to several floating gardens, which are an incredible sight to see. These gardens are made up of hundreds of individual floating pieces of land, which are anchored to the bottom of the lake. Theyre filled with vibrant flowers and provide a unique and beautiful addition to the already stunning scenery.

The people of Srinagar are also very proud of Dal Lake, and its clear to see why. They have taken great care to preserve and maintain the lake, and it shows. The water is clean and clear, and the surrounding area is well-maintained

name: Ankit Kothari
review_text:
Dal Lake is a beautiful lake located in Srinagar, Jammu & Kashmir, India. It is one of the most popular tourist destinations in India. The lake is surrounded by mountains and is known for its scenic beauty. It is also famous for its houseboats and shikaras (small boats) which are used for transportation and sightseeing.

Dal lake has its own history and importance as Srinagar is mainly located around it. Well for experience of Shikara it is worth a go or if you want to stay in one of the house boats. Dal Lake is almost the center of Srinagar. It is a large and beautiful lake. One can either stay at houseboats which are built in the lake (which I would not recommend), or take a shikara ride (boat ride). It is better to take a shikara ride for more than an hour, as one can also enjoy the floating shops and market in the lake.

Dal Lake has a rich history that dates back to the Mughal era when the emperor Jahangir visited the valley in the 17th century and was captivated by its natural beauty. He ordered the construction of several gardens and pavilions around the lake, which transformed the area into a paradise for nature lovers and royalty alike.

According to another source, there are basically two theories that suggest how the lake originated. One historical theory backed by geologists suggests that the lake is actually a post-glacial lake that formed after the Pleistocene period. While another theory suggests that the Dal lake simply formed from flood spillage.

review_text:
Dal Lake is a beautiful and iconic lake located in Srinagar, the capital city of the Indian state of Jammu and Kashmir. It is one of the most popular tourist destinations in the region, and its known for its serene beauty and breathtaking scenery.

The lake is surrounded by the majestic Himalayan mountains and is dotted with beautiful houseboats and shikaras (traditional Kashmiri boats). It covers an area of about 18 square kilometers and is one of the largest freshwater lakes in India.

Dal Lake is also an important source of livelihood for many locals, who rely on it for fishing and tourism. Visitors to the lake can take a shikara ride to explore its beautiful surroundings and also visit the floating gardens and markets that are set up on the lake.

Despite its popularity, the lake has faced various environmental challenges over the years, including pollution and encroachment. However, efforts are being made to preserve its beauty and protect its ecosystem.

name: Tourist Diary
review_text:
One of the most beautiful places to visit in India is the Dal Lake in Kashmir. Nestled in the Himalayan Mountains, the lake is a popular destination for tourists, both domestic and international.

The lake is situated in the Srinagar city of Kashmir, surrounded by the Zabarwan mountain range. It is one of the largest lakes in India, with a surface area of 18 square kilometers. It is fed by the Jhelum River and is connected to other bodies of water such as the Anchar Lake and the Nagin Lake.

The Dal Lake is known for its stunning beauty, with its crystal-clear waters surrounded by lush greenery and snow-capped mountains. The lake also has a number of floating gardens known as 'rad', where locals grow vegetables and fruits.

The best way to explore the Dal Lake is by taking a Shikara boat ride. These small boats take you around the lake, giving you stunning views of the surrounding landscape and the city of Srinagar. You can also explore the lake on foot, and enjoy a pleasant stroll along the banks.

name: JITU SHARMA
review_text:
Dal Lake is a picturesque lake located in Srinagar, the summer capital of the Indian state of Jammu and Kashmir. The lake is spread over an area of around 18 square kilometers and is surrounded by beautiful mountains and gardens.

The Dal Lake is known for its beautiful houseboats, which are essentially floating houses made of wood and decorated with intricate carvings and beautiful furnishings. The houseboats are a popular tourist attraction and offer a unique way to experience the beauty of the lake.

Apart from the houseboats, the Dal Lake is also known for its beautiful gardens, including the Shalimar Bagh, Nishat Bagh, and Chashme Shahi gardens. These gardens are famous for their colorful flowers and beautiful fountains, and are a popular destination for tourists visiting Srinagar.

The Dal Lake is also an important source of livelihood for the local people, who engage in activities such as fishing, agriculture, and handicrafts. The lake is home to a variety of fish species, including carp, trout, and mahseer.

Overall, Dal Lake is a beautiful and serene destination that offers a unique blend of natural beauty, culture, and history, making it a must-visit destination for tourists visiting Srinagar.

review_text:
Welcome - 2 - Jannat - E - Kashmir

Dal Lake is the second largest lake in Jammu and Kashmir, and the most visited place in Srinagar by tourists and locals. Dal Lake is also one of the best locations in Kashmir for film shooting.

It is also Known as the  Jewel in the Crown of Kashmir  &  Srinagar's Jewel  , Dal Lake is the most important landmark of Srinagar. It figures high on tourist itineraries and every tourist to the Kashmir valley makes it a point to visit .

The beauty of Dal Lake has attracted filmmakers and over 20 films have been shot in and around the famous water body.Mainstream Hindi films like, Junglee, Jab Jab Phool Khile, Kashmir Ki Kali, Jaanwar, Lamhaa, Yahaan, Mission Kashmir, Dil Se, Kabhi Kabhi, Rockstar and Yeh Jawaani Hai Deewani were shot or have scenes in which Dal Lake forms the backdrop.

The floating markets, shops, food stalls, morning vegitable markets , ATM of State Bank of India , Post Office etc attracts many of the tourists all around the world. Its really amazing & around lakhs of people are living and finding their daily income through this lake only.

I appeal to all the Tourist dont litter & Pollute this Lake.

name: Mohan Potaliya
review_text:
Dal Lake is a lake in Srinagar, the summer capital of the Indian state of Jammu and Kashmir. It is an important tourist attraction in the city, and is known for its houseboats, shikaras (traditional wooden boats), and Mughal gardens. The lake is also home to a variety of wildlife, including lotus flowers, birds, and fish. It is a popular spot for boating, fishing, and picnicking. The lake is located in the center of Srinagar and is surrounded by several neighborhoods and landmarks, including the Nehru Park, Shalimar Bagh, and the Hazratbal Mosque.

review_text:
Dal Lake is the most important landmark of Srinagar. During our family trip to 'Kashmir', we visited to 'Dal Lake' in Srinagar. Dal Lake is surrounded by beautiful gardens built in the Mughal era and many parks. Shikaras are a cultural symbol of the lake and seen mostly in the lakes of Srinagar. The best views of the lake can be seen from the Shalimar Garden and Nishat Garden.
The beauty of Dal Lake has been shot in and around the famous water body in number of films of bollywood. The films like, Junglee, Jab Jab Phool Khile, Kashmir Ki Kali, Mission Kashmir, Dil Se, Kabhi Kabhi, and Yeh Jawaani Hai Deewani were shot or have scenes in which Dal Lake forms the backdrop.

name: Anjana P B
review_text:
Dal is a lake in Srinagar, the summer capital of Jammu and Kashmir. It is an urban lake, the second largest lake in Jammu and Kashmir, and the most visited place in Srinagar by tourists and locals.Dal Lake is lined by gardens built in the Mughal era and many parks.
Mughals, who were smitten by the beauty of Kashmir, laid extensive gardens to heighten its beauty. The best views of the lake can be seen from the Shalimar Garden and Nishat Garden that were built during the reign of Mughal Emperor, Jehangir.

Shikaras are a cultural symbol of the lake and seen mostly in lakes of Srinagar. It is often called the Gondola of Kashmir and has achieved iconic status. While the boats are a part of daily life on the lake and used for a slew of purposes including transporting people and goods, it has become very popular with tourists. A ride on the lake is a must for tourists visiting Kashmir.

May to November is the best time to visit Dal Lake as the climate is pleasant. During winter, it gets extremely cold.

name: saima Choudhary
review_text:
The urban lake, is integral to tourism and recreation in Kashmir and is named the "Jewel in the crown of Kashmir" or "Srinagars Jewel". The lake is also an important source for commercial operations in fishing and water plant harvesting.
Especially when you are taking a Shikara trip across the Dal Lake, the cooling winds that caress you are a sensation like none other. Autumn /Monsoon is an ideal time to visit the city. Shikara ride is one of the most soothing, relaxing aspects of a holiday in Kashmir. Shikaras are long boats which crowd the Srinagar lakes. Dal Lake is famous for its beauty and tourists from every corner of the world visit Dal Lake on their visit to Kashmir. Dal lake is the second largest lake in the state.
This is what Emperor Jehangir is reported to have said soulfully about Kashmir - If there is paradise on Earth, it is here, it is here, it is here. Really Dal is heaven.

With houseboats which are stilted firmly on a temporary structure, there is a host of house boats lined up right next to each other all acros the lake. With some water plants growing around the boats and vendors selling saffron and flowers on the shikharas and kayaks all around, the experience of staying on the dal lake is a must do for anyone who enjoys travel. There are also markets floating around selling a lot of handicraft fare such as carpets and winter jackets and pashmina shawl and the likes.

name: Priya P
review_text: The iconic Dal Lake situated in the heart of Srinagar, once known for is natural beauty is now being exploited by the commercial houseboats. We stayed in such a houseboat for one night, being the first time, the bucket list worthy experience was new. The best part was watching sunrise from the porch, and having hot Kashmiri khawa from a boat seller. We shifted to a houseboat on Nigeen lake for the next day, and it was beautiful and romantic. We came back to Dal lake for sunset shikara ride but they charged exorbitant prices starting at Rs. 2000 for one hour ride amongst hundreds of crowded shikara all around. But our houseboat on Nigeen lake then arranged for one hour complimentary shikara ride and it was a wonderful memory of a lifetime. I would recommend staying on Nigeen lake instead as it was quiet, peaceful and less crowded.

name: MALIK AHSAN
review_text:
Jewel in the crown of kashmir, This beautiful lake with multi-faceted ecosystem, is the second largest lake in the state, and covers an area of about 18 sq km. It is popular for unique houseboats and shikara rides that form the identity of the lake. Apart from the houseboat and shikara rides, one can enjoy kayaking, canoeing, water surfing and licensed angling on the lake with the prior permission of the lake authority.The lake is encircled by magnificent mountains on three sides. This Himalayan lake has 5 basins and several channels, which are well linked with each other. The blooming Mughal gardens and Orchards on the banks contribute a lot to the beauty of the Dal Lake. These colourful gardens and lawns were established in 16th and 17th century, but the tourism department has still maintained the natural beauty of these lawns.

The flora of the lake includes lotus, lillies and water chestnuts. While on a boat ride in Dal Lake, one may also notice birds like kingfishers and herons. If you plan to visit the Dal lake in summers, you might find it laden with lotuses while in winters you might find the lake frozen and covered with snow.

About:
Dal is a lake in Srinagar, the summer capital of Jammu and Kashmir. It is an urban lake, the second largest lake in Jammu and Kashmir, and the most visited place in Srinagar by tourists and locals. It is integral to tourism and recreation in the Kashmir valley and is variously known as the Lake of Flowers,Jewel in the crown of Kashmir or Srinagars Jewel. The lake is also an important source for commercial operations in fishing and water plant harvesting.

name: vysakh shine
review_text:
A must visit place if you are to Kashmir. Dal lake is the icon of Kashmir. A ride in shikhara boats on the waters of dal lake is one which makes your Kashmir journey unforgettable.
I visited Kashmir in the month of September which was an off tourist season. Hence ride for 1 person for an hour and half costs me Rs 150.
There was 3 other people on the boat. That is approximately Rs 500 for a boat ride for 1 and hour hour.

The boat ride was an amazing experience. The view of Pirpanjal mountain ranges surrounding Kashmir was spectacular. While riding many local people with their shikharas approaches our boat and try to sell local made stuffs.This was a good experience. But dont bargain with them else or try buying stuffs from them else your peaceful mood will be spoiled.

Theyll take you to a floating market. And this was also a good experience.

review_text:
Its a great natural beauty in Shrinagar.
Its very big 7.44 x 3.5 km , depths veries from 2.5 to 6 metres (aere 22 sq km ) , natural water reservoir, its an inflow source of Jhelum river.
 Its a main water source of Shrinagar.
There are many house boats for stay day and night.. These house boats have stars according to the facilities they provide. Its very nice experience to stay in the house boats.
Shikara ride in Dal lake is an amazing experience. Its better to select evening time for this ride. It takes one to two hours depending upon you select the places to watch. We have gone to floating market ( reasonable price ) , vegetable garden, water sports area.
Those who love water sports, can do water scooter, jet ski .
 Overall experience in the evening Shikara ride is beyond imagination... Amazing nature...
Very peaceful.. During shikara ride, many sellers come to sell something like jwellery, wooden items etc. But if you want to enjoy the ride, tell your boatman that you dont want to get disturbed by these people. Then the boatman help you.

name: Prathamesh Avachare
review_text:
When in Srinagar, I got to experience the soothing Shikara Ride at Dal Lake. This hillside lake is home to the wonderfully carved wooden houseboats and colorful Shikaras (the small wooden carved boats) casually commuting through the scenic peaks of the Pir Panjal Mountains. It is spread across 22 square kilometers and its beauty kept growing as my Shikarawala rowed my Shikara deeper and deeper into its placid water flow!

Shikaras are extensively used to commute back and forth from the houseboats, for daily traveling, or for boating tours. They are very well maintained, beautifully decorated, and rowed by professionals who are well aware of the different aspects of Dal Lake, which makes the Shikara Rides even more exciting and interesting. Staying rooted in their old charm, the swift movement of a Shikara provided me with a unique way to experience the eternal beauty of Kashmir, and must say, they certainly add to the beauty of Dal Lake with their colorful presence!

The duration of the Shikara Ride at Dal Lake in Kashmir ranges from 1 hour to 4 hours, the Shikarawalas at one of the ghats surrounding the lake guided me regarding the same which helped me in choosing the ride as per my convenience. However, the pricing here is dynamic so the better your bargaining skills, the better chances of you bagging a worthy deal!

It was an experience of a lifetime for me as I got wooed by scenic vistas of the Zabarwan Range and the deepness of the calming Dal Lake. The vibrations in the water formed by the rowing of Shikarawala were an equally visual treat. The mesmerizing scene of surrounding snowy mountains looked even more beautiful at the sunset which reflected in the gleaming water of the lake.

The Shikara ride is incomplete without stopping at Meena Bazaar, a lively lake market. This market has a number of shops selling all sorts of goods including Kashmir's specialties such as wooden artifacts, handmade earrings, carpets, Kashmiri handicrafts, saffron, and even Kashmiri Pashmina shawls right in the middle of the lake. However, it is advisable to avoid shopping here as the rates are on the higher side and the authenticity of goods sold is doubtful.

Dal Lake is nothing short of heaven for film shootings and photography enthusiasts. May it be its floating gardens or the lush green spread around and the rocky terrains, it has various sights to offer for you to get those perfect shots! Besides this, I also got to see various birds while enjoying my ride which was indeed a cheerful sight.

A Shikara ride is the best way to enjoy a picturesque ride across the lake, especially because these wooden boats with pointed ends on both sides and with beautiful canopies overhead are a cultural symbol and can only be seen in Srinagar.

Must say, this ride helped me build memories of a lifetime, and was worth every penny. Spending a day in the calm waters of Dal Lake was one of the most relaxing aspects of my Kashmir Trip. It was hard to bid farewell to this delightful ride which made me fall in love with every nook and corner of the iconic Dal Lake against the backdrop of the snow-covered mountains but I'm definitely carrying a smile on my face, calmness of mind, the coolness of emotions and a heart filled with gratitude with me!

The house boats stay is other thing you should not miss when you are in Srinagar.
You can find a lot of house boats here.

Most scenic place of Srinagar is nothing but Dal Lake. Situated in the heart of Srinagar, this place has so many beautiful points to visit. The sunrise and sunset views at Dal lake are something you should never miss. Visit to the floating market, Lotus Farms, Village located on the lake, water sport activities and many more things on Shikara (Boat) ride. The on the go market is best thing about Shikara ride. It takes approx 3 hours to visit all the important points of Dal lake. People of Kashmir are sweet as sugar, the Shikara rider shares thousands of memories and things happened around the Dal lake, which makes the Shikara journey joyful.
Also do consider staying at Dal lake Houseboats, spend a night here to feel the breeze and awesome ambience of the Scenic Dal Lake.

name: RAMITA DUTTA
review_text: Known as the Jewel in the Crown of Kashmir and Srinagar's Jewel, Dal Lake is the most important landmark of Srinagar. It figures high on tourist itineraries and every tourist to the Kashmir valley makes it a point to visit the water body. There are two theories for the origin of the lake - one states that it is a post-glacial lake that has undergone a lot of changes in size over the years. The other theory of the origin of the lake states that the Dal Lake was formed due to flood spillage from the Jhelum River.

name: Kartikeya Sharma
review_text:
Dal Lake is one of the main tourist attraction in Srinagar. The Shikara ride is relaxing. The are some sellers that you might encounter in the Dal Lake who sell different stuff like shawls, show pieces, jewellery, kesar, shilajit etc on the boat. Also, there is a market in the vicinity of the lake where you can buy local items that are famous in Srinagar like Kesar, Shawls, artefacts made of wood etc.
However, there is one thing which I did not like about the lake. The lake is not clean and it seems like you are boating in water full of moss, plastic & food waste floating around, some parts of the lake smells like sewer. I did not even put my hand in the water during the course if 1hr shikara ride.

However, there are some water cleaning boats that are cleaning the floating moss and plastic waste but the lake is so big that it will not make big difference.

The point is that we are responsible to keep our surroundings clean and we can expect only so much support from authorities.

name: ashu yadav
review_text: Dal Lake is a famous lake in Srinagar, Kashmir. Spread over an area of   18 kilometers, this lake is surrounded by hills on three sides. This is the second largest lake of Jammu and Kashmir. Water comes from springs and also many lakes of Kashmir Valley come into it. Its four major reservoirs are Gagribal, Lokut Dal, Bod Dal and Nagin. Roopalank Island is situated in the middle of Lokut Dal and Sonalank Island is situated in the middle of Bod Dal stream. It is named among the most beautiful lakes of India. The beauty of Dal Lake is visible from the nearby Mughal garden. It is not possible for tourists to come to Jammu and Kashmir and not visit Dal Lake.

name: Milind Kocharekar
review_text:
Dal lake is situated at Srinagar. It is also called as the heart of Srinagar.
DAL lake is covered with snow-capped mountains surrounding three of its sides, signature Kashmiri style houseboats and colorful shikaras that afloat the lake and the stunning Mughal gardens and orchards lined on its banks. Overlooking the lake are two hillocks that house the Shankaracharya and Hari Parbat temples. Yes, that is just how picturesque the Dal lake is. And the Dal lake images are a testimony to this fact.
Moreover, the floating gardens on the Dal have a magic of their own. They are an ecological system in the lake. Farmers residing here are dedicated to growing crops and vegetables on this lake. Over 6,000 families depend on these floating gardens for their livelihood. The produce obtained is then sold in local markets throughout Srinagar.
Its beauty hasn't just attracted tourists all over the world but quite a lot of filmmakers as well. As many as 20 films have been shot in and around this area. Some of the most popular ones include Kashmir ki Kali, Lamhaa, Kabhi Kabhi and Dil se- among many others.
Whenever you find yourself in Srinagar, make sure to visit the Dal lake early in the morning. I guarantee you that it is an experience that you'll remember and cherish forever

review_text:
Dal is a lake in Srinagar, the summer capital of Jammu and Kashmir. It is an urban lake, the second largest lake in Jammu and Kashmir, and the most visited place in Srinagar by tourists and locals.

It is integral to tourism and recreation in the Kashmir valley and is variously known as the Lake of Flowers, Jewel in the crown of Kashmir or Srinagars Jewel.

This place have house boat and floating markets. Also have floating "Post Office". As per locals says there are almost 400 thousands people lives in dal lake area.

There is 3 to 8 visiting sites available. 40 min to 2 hours it will take to visit normally. For the boat rent you need negotiate to get by best cost.

name: Gaurav Thakur
review_text: Definitely a mesmerising lake and a must visit place in Srinagar. If youre in Srinagar, dont forget to take a ride on a Shikara (boat) on the Dal lake. Its a very big lake, really very big. The lake also has houseboats, which from inside, are truly exemplary and classy. I stayed in the houseboat named New Australia on the last day of my tour and it was so beautiful that I really regretted spending all my nights in the hotels. It was very beautiful. Were given Shikara and houseboat by our travel agency, so I dont know about the pricing. But the Shikara takes you to upto Meena Bazar after that they charge extra for further ride into the area ahead. Jet ski is also available but near the Nishat garden area only. You can also have a walk on the sidewalks made on the circumference of the lake. I urge the government to clean the algae from Lake water.

review_text: My recent visit to dal lake was fabulous ans mesmerizing. The lake is total in 22square km and the shikaras in it makes more attractive. But now a days people who live around dal lake are filling this wetland for illegal construction. The authorities of conversation of wetlands are trying there best to stop illegal acts. However from last one decade the dal lake is getting more and more polluted if we look from dal gate end there are polythene bags, wine bottles, junk food wrappers etc in it. This beautiful lake of srinagar has become a dumping site and people living in houseboats have contructed toilets in it that has changed its PH level which leads to extinction of marine life as water becomes more acidy.

review_text: Dal is a lake in Srinagar, the summer capital of Jammu and Kashmir. It is the second largest lake in Jammu and Kashmir, and the most visited place in Srinagar by tourists and locals. It is integral to tourism and is variously known as the Lake of Flowers, Jewel in the crown of Kashmir or Srinagars Jewel. The shikaras(mini boats) rides you through the lake and will show beautiful version of the lake. Shikara owner can take around 1000 to 1500 depends on pick time for almost 2 hours per shikara. Shikara owner will take to the market in Lake but dont purchase anything that will be costlier. Other venders in the lake also spoils the fun of enjoyment by interrupting frequently.

name: Mr. jareda
review_text:
Dal Lake is considered the jewel of Srinagar. Spread over 26 square kilometers, this lake is like heaven on earth. It is situated amidst beautiful green mountains. Facilities like shikara boat rides, house boats and lake markets make this place a favorite among tourists. Srinagar has always been a pleasant place to visit in summer. Therefore it is one of the favorite places of the Mughals and the British. Tourists can enjoy house boat on Dal Lake.

Let us tell you that the concept of house boat on Dal Lake was the brainchild of the British, which promoted tourism. Whenever you plan to visit Srinagar, make Dal Lake the first priority in your list. Because if there is any lake here that is most beautiful and captivating, then it is Dal Lake. Let us take you on a trip to Dal Lake Srinagar through this article.

You never visited kashmir if you have not taken shikara ride in dal lake.

Awesome experience of shikara ride in clear and peaceful waters of dal lake. We took evening shikara and had opportunity to witness sunset. One hour ride was such soul satisfying that it made is feel the beauty of Kashmir Valley.

On the ride various vendors like kabab wala, kahwa wala, photographers, Maggie wala, chat wala, etc will meet you on the way and offer you the things. Its an unique experience all together.

All shikara will take you to market in between dal lake. Nice experience of it though we didnt buy anything.

Shikara accommodate around 4 adults and 2 kids. Costs around 1000 rs for one hour ride.

Worth it.

name: Suriya Gayathri
review_text: Dal is an urban lake which is integral to tourism and recreation in Kashmir and is named the 'Jewel in the crown of Kashmir'. The lake is also an important source for commercial operations in fishing and water plant harvesting. The shoreline of the lake, is about 24 kilometres and is encompassed by a boulevard lined with Mughal era gardens, parks, houseboats and hotels. The lake is part of a natural wetland which has floating gardens. It blossoms with lotus flowers during July and August. The shikara ride on Dal Lake is a must-to-do activity if you are in Srinagar. It is a delightful experience to have the cruise in the evenings. There are also numerous houseboats parked along the shores of Dal Lake which provide accommodation to tourists in Srinagar.

name: Anil Singh
review_text:
The lake is on one periphery of Srinagar city and is a delight to behold. It has evolved and improved over the years thanks to the zealous preservation work done by tourism, municipal and environment departments.
All the Mughal gardens are in its vicinity, be it Shalimar, Chashma Shahi or even Nishat which is at a small distance.
The lake had shrunk over the years due to encroachment on all sides but now they are being retrieved.

Shopping like ornaments, kesar, photos, gifts, clothes, photography etc (be ready for the bargain). Normally they charge 800 to 1000 for a 2 hour ride. You will need atleast 2 hours for this ride.
USP - Dal Lake is one of the biggest lake of the world and the biggest in India that makes it so special.
Visit - As per me its a must visit for every tourist in srinagar, infact we found Dal Lake to be one of the major reason to visit srinagar.

name: Harpreet Bains
review_text:
A jewel in the crown that Srinagar beholds, it lies on the foot of the Mount Shridhara. Dal is a vast stretch of water shimmering on the carved wooden balconies of the houseboats and the misty peaks of the Pir Panjal Mountains; the lake is divided by causeways into 4 parts. The floating gardens on which the lotuses blossom during July and August are to look for.

The urban lake, is integral to tourism and recreation in Kashmir and is named the "Jewel in the crown of Kashmir" or "Srinagars Jewel". The lake is also an important source for commercial operations in fishing and water plant harvesting
Dal Lake is lined by gardens built in the Mughal era and many parks. Mughals, who were smitten by the beauty of Kashmir, laid extensive gardens to heighten its beauty. The best views of the lake can be seen from the Shalimar Garden and Nishat Garden that were built during the reign of Mughal Emperor, Jehangir.

name: Arun M
review_text: Dal Lake, the second largest and most beautiful lake in Jammu and Kashmir, is in Srinagar, the most popular tourist attraction in Jammu and Kashmir. We spent 2 nights at Dal Lake instead of staying in Srinagar. It was the best day of our 8-day trip. We did a wonderful Shikara cruise through the lake. While cruising, we experienced the scenic beauty, the reflection of mountains in the water, and a wonderful sunset where the sky changes colour. There are a lot of floating shops where you will find different antique collections. There are small boats that sell tasty barbecued chicken, fish, and paneer, etc. Close to the road that leads to Dal Lake dock, you can find a lot of street vendors who sell winter clothes, jackets, antique collections, dresses, and foods. If we bargain more, you may get it for a very low cost. Still, I think these are the lowest priced winter jackets and gloves available compared to Delhi or other places. If you are planning to visit Jammu and Kashmir in the winter, you should buy your winter clothes here for a cheaper price than elsewhere. There are some good restaurants that have tasty food. Never miss the opportunity to stay at Dal Lake, at least for one night. Not everyone likes to spend more than one night at the lake, as we need to take a shikara to reach the road and come back to the houseboat. Our houseboat offered complimentary drop-off and pick-up service to the dock and vice versa. I really miss Dal Lake and Srinagar and will come back in the future.

review_text:

The lake is also an important source for commercial operations in fishing and water plant harvesting.

The key features and the tourism attractions are the boat house, the floating market, the neharu garden, the crystal clear water of the lake. The shikara rides is just wonderful one can spent a whole day in the shikara enjoying the kashmiri kavha.

review_text: World famous for its splendid beauty, the lake is perfectly located in the heart of the city at the foothills of Zabarwan mountain range. Adding to the charisma is the presence of Historic Mughal Gardens on its banks. One of the most beautiful Golf Courses in the world, the Royal Springs Golf Course, is also situated on its banks. An International Convention Centre, SKICC, is also located at its periphery. It is frequented by tourists during all seasons. Theres a while lot to see and do. Ranging from Shikara rides, water sports, to a stay in the awesome houseboats that dot its facade, a stroll in the floating market, a visit to a small island in the middle of the lake, Char Chinar, everything is just surreal. Its a must visit for any trip to Kashmir. However of late pollution and massive encroachments have somewhat choked it at some places.

You can ask the driver of the car to rent a houseboat. He will manage the houseboat according to your budget.

A trip to Dal Lake is one of the highlights of my life.

The shikara ride was very good. There are multiple options - 30 mins, 1 hr, 2hrs etc. We took 1 hour ride, and it was fantastic. The views are breathtaking.
Its one of the best place around in Srinagar. The walk around banks of Dal Lake , the fishing experience, the shikara rides, the boat house stays, the shopping in its floating market, the lightining fountain view at night, the view of zabarwan hills, the sun rise and sunset view and it goes on, everything has its unique experience. This lake is a heart of Srinagar valley and we are lucky to have it.

name: Muneeb Najar
review_text:
Dal Lake has rightfully become an icon of the Kashmir tourism industry. A Himalayan urban lake, it has five basins and a number of channels that are well linked with each other. There are plenty of fishes in Dal Lake and fishery is the second largest industry of the region centered on the lake. The sparkling quiet waters of Dal surrounded by snow-capped mountains on its three sides, undoubtedly mark it as one of the most beautiful lakes of India. It is also the second largest lake in the State of Jammu and Kashmir with numerous gardens and orchards all along its shores. Houseboats form an indelible part of the scenery of the Dal Lake that are always ready to take tourists to a romantic and peaceful ride of the lake and soothe their nerves as the houseboat floats over the slightly rippling waters. They also offer some of the most exotic views of the splendid scenery of the Dal Lake.

There are Shikaras that look like small ornate versions of the gondolas of Venice that offers ferry rides to and from the banks of the lake to the houseboats. The shores of the Lake houses the distinct Moghul monuments and the campus of the Kashmir University while the two hillocks overlooking the lake house Shankar Acharya and Hari Parbat temples. The glorious Mughal gardens on its shores contribute to the beauty of the Dal Lake. Out of about five hundred gardens laid down in 16th to 17th century, only a few still survive. There have been controversies about the origin of the Dal Lake. While some geologists believe that the origins of Dal Lake lie in the Pleistocene Oligotrophic Lake that once covered the entire valley of Kashmir, others just believe it to be a flood plain lake. The floating gardens of Dal Lake are considered a beauty in themselves. One can find a number of restaurants and hotels at the lakefront that have sprung up, encouraged by the large influx of tourists here.

name: Mahuya Acharya
review_text:
There will be 4 different seasonal look of this lake based on seasons. The shore line of the lake, about 15.5 kilometres is encompassed by a boulevard lined with Mughal era gardens, houseboats and hotels. Scenic views of the lake can be witnessed from the shore line Mughal gardens, such as Shalimar Bagh and Nishat Bagh built during the reign of Mughal Emperor Jahangir and from houseboats cruising along the lake in the colourful shikaras. During the winter season, the temperature sometimes reaches 11 degC (12 degF), freezing the lake.

The lake covers an area of 18 SQ kimi and is part of a floating gardens. The floating gardens, known as Rad in Kashmiri, blossom with lotus flowers during July and August. The wetland is divided by causeways into four basins; Gagribal, Lokut Dal, Bod Dal and Nigeen (although Nigeen is also considered as an independent lake).
A small island called char chinar is present mid of the lake. Though one chinar tree died.

Dal is mentioned as Mahasarit (Sanskrit-mhaasrit) in ancient Sanskrit texts. Ancient history records mention that a village named Isabar to the east of Dal was the residence of goddess Durga.

review_text:
The Dal lake is a mesmerizing view in itself especially once you are on the water. Some parts especially are very scenic. And fortunately it is not yet dirtied with rubbish thrown by tourists.

The shikara ride at Dal lake is a good experience. It can be done from around 20-25 different places around the lake. Better start from an empty spot to enjoy the most. The travel guys generally take you to a relatively crowded place. And then u r flocked by ppl trying to sell u things on the boat. Ur shikara guy might take u to a shop where u can buy warm clothes, shawls etc, but its a waste of time. Dont get lured into booking more than an hour. They kill time by forcing u to enter different shops. Each extra hour of the shikara is about rs 1000

name: Bhat Moin
review_text:
Srinagar, the summer capital of Jammu and Kashmir stands on Dal Lake and the river Jhelum. This ancient city was founded by Emperor Asoka when his daughter Charumati took a fancy to Dal Lake during a pilgrimage to the area. The present city was established by the King Raja Pravarsen II in the 6th century. Its name was derived from the old name Suryanagar (The city of Surya or the Sun God).
It had a strategic as well as economic importance as it stands on the ancient trade route to Central Asia Srinagar is the most populous city, covering an area of about 28.5 sq km. The river Jhelum, flanked by the Dal lake and intersected by canals, runs through the city and lends an idyllic charm to it.
Snow capped mountains, romantic houseboats, sunny gardens, simmering lakes aesthetic beauty, rich culture, historical monuments and refreshing Kawah is what Srinagar overview is all about. The weather in Srinagar is alpine. Summers (April-June) are mild and winters are cold (November-February). It experiences heavy snowfall in December - February. The best time to visit Srinagar is during summers between April and June.

name: Daanish Mohiuddin (EANU)
review_text:
The lake is popular as a visitor attraction and a summer resort. Fisheries and the harvesting of food and fodder plants are also important on Dal.Weeds from the lake are extracted and converted into compost for the gardens. It also serves as a flood lung of the Jhelum River. Swimming, boating, snow skiing (particularly when the lake is frozen during the severe winter), and canoeing are amongst some of the water sports activities practised on the lake.

The lake has numerous sites and places of interest, many of which are important to the cultural heritage of Srinagar. Aside from the Shalimar Bagh and Nishat Bagh, some of the other places frequented by tourists are the Shankaracharya temple, the Hari Parbat, the Nigeen Lake, the Chashme Shahi, the Hazratbal Shrine, and the Mazar-e-Shura cemetery containing the graves of famous Mughal-era poets. Visitors and native alike also enjoy relaxing on the water in a houseboat or a shikara boat, often called the Gondola of Kashmir.

I urge you to take a shikara ride for 2 hrs,it will cover most of the lake, will take you through shops in canals which are in the lake. There are vegetable and fruit vendors on boats. In summertime one can see mountain ranges from the lake itself. No washrooms are available. There are multiple gates and gates are called as ghat.

review_text: Dal lake is a central location of Srinagar in Jammu and Kashmir  Dal lake waterways Development Authority also known as LWDA responsible for managing the lakes cleaning and maintenance. Lake serves for composting of weeds and phytoplankton for the gardens of Mughal and tulips near by dal Lake. One can see the magical experience of it either running, walking or taking shikara ride. The area of Srinagar is urban and its colorful eye-catching experience make you be in the Natural Home  floating boats and hotels are on the way to host many tourists here. Recently Dal lake became the first of kind cinema hall over floating around where bollywood movie shown and people enjoyed entertainment while under the open sky

name: Eber Shibin
review_text: A decent experience. In my view, it was a little overrated. It could be because when you hire a Shikara and start from Dalgate, its a a bit of a drag until you enter the main area, thats where it widens into an open landscape which is lovely to watch. The lakes have got algae all the way upto the surface, so it doesn't give you the best feeling, but I also feel it could be because tourism is still in revival phase as a result of Covid-19 and maintenance wasnt done regularly. I arrived from Mumbai and got this out of the bucket list on the arrival day itself. U can lay back and relax on the Shikara and maximize your visiting places in Kashmir for the remainder of your stay. Watch out for hawkers cornering your Shikara every possible chance and offering goods for sale. Recommended to avoid them - whether its handicrafts or kebabs or photos in local costumes. The ride through the lake is not worth it for more than 2 hrs max. The Shikara riders show points which are to be enjoyed in person not gawked at from the lake. Only go for places situated on the lake, detox yourself for a solid 2 hrs and go back.

Then the shikara person took us on Lake tour. We saw many shikara shops on our way and we bought few things from them we also had chicken tikka from one shikara shop it was delicious. We had kesar kava. We saw meena bazar which was on shikaras. Saw shikara boats for the first time in life. It was very nice experience overall. name: Travelnindia
review_text: It is a great place to relax. In summers, it is recommended to take the Shikara ride in the evening as afternoons can be hot. One has to be very careful while visiting for the first time as Shikara owners ask for huge sums for a simple ride. The price is not more than Rs.200 for half An hour but they always quote 1700 or even more. Also another annoying thing is the hawkers pestering you while you enjoy the Shikara ride. Everything they sell is cheap and fake so dont pay a dime for it. It is absolutely ok to be be dismissive even if you think you are being rude. The near by Nigeen lake is a quieter and cleaner option for boating as well as House boat stay. If you can manage the crooks, it is a great experience.

The lake is b-e-a-u-t-i-f-u-l but the crowd is not. Better crowd management is required around the lake banks.
The eutrophication is really overwhelming when you take Shikara rides, ruins your experience. Overall, a very peaceful lake for boating and to chill. Moreover, public littering is a big problem.

name: Trupthi Trupsy
review_text:
Dal lake is yet another must visit place in jammu and Kashmir..
This is the beauty to be merismised in a shikari ride... We were so amazed with this place that we visited twice. once we took a morning ride and another one was in the evening.
You will find the floating markets, many sellers keep selling the goods in their boats.. You can even click pics wearing kashmir attire phiran... Hard copies of the photos will be given once we finish our ride..
Shikari ride makes you feel you are floating in middle of the lake.. Its such a peaceful and stress buster ride..
As my our expirence please be beware of localities they try to loot you... Never buy the plant seeds which they sell it will never germinate..
We visited this place exact 2 years back..

name: SURENDER SINGH
review_text:
Dal lake is perhaps one of the most famous and scenic lakes in all of India. Situated in Srinagar in Kashmir, Dal Lake stretches to a length of around 7 kms with a width of 3.5 kms. Since Moghul times Dal Lake has been an attraction because of its beauty and aptly named 'Jewel in the crown of Kashmir'

As seen in many Bollywood films, the Dal Lake is pristine with floating gardens, house boats and shikaras. Around 30 percent of the lake is covered with lotus plants. The Dal Lake makes Srinagar a popular tourist spot. Since the British times, the Houseboats are of immense tourist attraction. These houseboats are large boats with luxurious rooms and sprawling decks for sunbathing. These boats are usually anchored on the shores. The shikaras or the small boats form the means of transportation to the houseboats and islands and also of smaller commercial activities on the lake. They are also popular for taking spending leisure time and taking a boat ride on among the gardens.

Commercial activities on Dal Lake

Tourism is of course the biggest commercial activity. The lake is surrounded by picturesque boulevards. The other attractions at the lake include the island with four Cedars, named Char Chinar. The Shalimar gardens along the lake and the smaller Nagin Lake also attracts many tourists.

For religious travellers the Hazratbal shrine is a much frequented place, as also the Shankaracharya Temple.

The floating gardens are made out of earth with matted roots but they are not anchored to the bottom of the lake. They are used for growing vegetables like cucumbers and others that need a lot of water. The water of Dal Lake being nutrient-rich, plants thrive on it.

Problems with Dal Lake

Pollution from the sewers and other dumps has become a problem for the lake over the last few decades but is being met successfully.

Eutrophication is the other big problem because of the high nutrients found in the water. The excessive growth of plants and algae on the surface form a green cover and the water surface gets hidden. This too is being dealt with especially from the large investment made by the government of India for the restoration of the lake.

Dal Lake is an important lake not just for its beauty but also from a religious point of view for many Indians, its shores supposed to be the residence of Goddess Durga.

name: Travel my kashmir
review_text:
5 stars for the Dal lake. Its a unique in its own kind. Dal Lake is situated in the heart of the srinagar city. The Lake is the main attraction for the tourist in srinagar.

Dal Lake Morphology :
Visitors may be surprised to find that Dal Lake is a single body of water as it has the appearance of being many different lakes and pools interconnected and divided by numerous causeways, buildings on stilts, floating gardens and houseboats.
The lake is actually formed from five lake basins these being the Nehru Park, Nishat, Hazratbal, Nagin and Brari. The lake is shallow with a depth of around 6m and it currently has an area of around 16 sq km although it has previously covered an area of around 22 sq km.

Access to Dal Lake:
Being an urban lake, it is easily accessible with roads running around it and reaching this part of the world is fairly easy with a good road network and an airport just 7 km away at Badgam. It should be noted however that no rail service operates in this region.

Dal Lake House Boats
The first houseboats appeared during the days of British colonial rule when the beauty of this part of the country lured many of the British but the Maharaja of Kashmir strictly controlled the building of houses. The British overcame such restrictions by simply taking to the water. Each of the early houseboats were built in a particularly British style leading to them being described as "each a little piece of England". Today's houseboats continue to offer accommodation and style seemingly from an earlier age. Many visitors choose to stay at one of these unique floating homes but there are also good quality hotels and restaurants on the lake-front.
Spending time on the water is a priority for most people and one of the favourite modes of transport is the shikava boat which has been described as the gondola of Kashmir. The owners of houseboats invariably provide shikavas for the use of their guests and others are available for hire at reasonable, although usually negotiable, rates.

What to See at Dal Lake:
There are many interesting places to visit such as the ancient temple of Shankaracharya or the masses of lotus flowers which bloom in July and August. The lake also has many floating gardens often moored in close proximity to the houseboats. These gardens are created from sections of matted vegetation which are simply cut free and manoeuvred into position. Perhaps unsurprisingly, water loving crops such as melons, cucumbers and tomatoes seem to grow particularly well in these conditions.
There is always a great deal of activity on the lake and it even hosts a floating market where vendors sell their produce, directly from their boats. In some areas, swimming is popular as is canoeing and other forms of boating. During the winter months, there may even be the opportunity for skiing.

When to Visit Dal Lake
The most popular time to visit Dal Lake is between June and August when the weather is probably at its most pleasant. Average summer temperatures range from 12 to 30 degrees Celsius making this a pleasant escape from the scorching summer temperatures found in much of India. Most people seem to agree with the old Maharaja on his choice of summer retreat.

Winter however has its own attractions and this is when the spectacular scenery can be experienced at its magnificent best. Winter temperatures average around 1 to 11 degrees Celsius but during a harsh winter, temperatures can drop as low as minus 11 degrees and at such temperatures, the surface of the lake can freeze. Needless to say, venturing onto the frozen surface can be extremely dangerous and should not be attempted without taking specialist advice from local experts.

Perhaps the most defining feature of the lake from the point of view of tourism is the sight of hundreds of houseboats moored close to the shorelines.The first houseboats appeared during the days of British colonial rule when the beauty of this part of the country lured many of the British but the Maharaja of Kashmir strictly controlled the building of houses. name: Sagar Rock
review_text:
Dal Lake and Kashmiri hospitality

It is difficult to find a person who has been to Srinagar but has not ridden a shikara at Dal Lake. That area of   Dal Lake looks so wonderful that no matter how many times you visit it, it never gets old. It is very fun to walk along the long road called Boulevard Road by the lake. Shikaras are roaming in the wobbly water of the lake, rows of houseboats floating in the water are waiting for tourists, rows of mountains in the far distance, four Chinas like an island in the middle of the lake will keep you enthralled. When I went to Kashmir for the first time in 1989, Kashmir was very calm, the riots had not yet started. We used to leave Srinagar every morning and visit Pahelgao, Gulmarg and Shonmarg and return to Srinagar at the end of the day. Even then we had no idea how turbulent Kashmir was going to be in a few years. Then in 2010, when I went to Leh by car from Srinagar, I did not go to Pahelgao or Gulmarg. I had the eyes of a service bird, so I didnt want to go anywhere else to waste time or hurt my body. Because there was a huge impassable road ahead, more than 1000 km. It was starting from Srinagar, going around Leh and returning via Manali, Chandigarh. We stayed in Srinagar for three days. Visited Shankaracharya Temple, Mughal Garden and Dal Lake. There was a lot of chaos in Kashmir at that time. All around the army is standing guard with raised rifles. A funny incident happened while riding Shikara at Dal Lake. It was the end of May. At that time, the tourists in Srinagar have decreased a lot, because the monsoons have almost started, but this is the ideal time to visit Leh. We took Shikara for an hour in the afternoon, she was supposed to turn things around, her name seems to be Sahel. At the back of the lake, many shopkeepers have set up their shops. Beyond them the hunters are advancing deeper. It was almost evening and the place was so deserted that my Ginni got up and screamed in fear, what is the mans intention, tell him to turn the hunters at once etc. Seeing that there was no one else around, I was also a little nervous. I asked Sahel in a harsh voice to quickly turn Shikara. He must have understood something, he just said like Babuji Doro Mat, Aplog Hamara Mehman. I was very ashamed to hear this. In fact there is no comparison to the customs or hospitality of real Kashmiris. I have never been in any danger by trusting them.

name: Sanjay Gupta
review_text:
Dal Lake in Srinagar Kashmir is a beautiful place that should visit at a time in your life. People are very friendly over there. I was there for 3 days and enjoyed the ride of 7-8 shikaras day & Night. Other shikaras passing by you sell snacks-beers and all kinds of stuff. I also stayed in the houseboat, it was an altogether different experience. that houseboat was so beautiful, a wooden piece of art.

The surrounding environment around the lake is interesting with beautiful scenery that good for spending time relaxing there. Mornings will never be the same again after u wake up to the sun rising over the beautiful Dal Lake. Life is laid back easy and also beautiful. Lake itself is beautiful with colorful boats, scenic mountains in the background, and many shops in boats. The best time is to take around the evening 1 hour before the sunset when the lake is quiet and the weather is nice. Dal lake itself is quite huge and provides some stunning views. If you are in Srinagar, this is a must-visit.

there are many ghats ( kind of Taxi Stop stand), starting from 1 to 16.. I was there at Ghat-12...

Be careful with shopping recommendations by the drivers. They literally force you to buy. also, there is a floating market, where shikara riders will take you. just like Bangkok and other countries floating market,

Better go to Lal Chowk.
I want to share my experience with one shikara rider. As everyone knows the Kashmir issue and how people over there support Pakistan. The rider asked me, aur Sahab Ji, aapka desh kaisa hai  (Sir, how is your country). I was shocked as I told him, is Kashmir in another country and then we argued for 5 minutes, my elder brother make me shut up and said teasingly, don't argue with fool, he ll drown his boat and you can't do anything. Chill, Enjoy

name: Murtaza Mushtaq
review_text:
Awesome place 
Main features:
Reckoned to be the pride of Kashmir tourism, Dal Lake is the most popular attraction in Srinagar. Enclosed by splendid Pir Panjal mountains and Mughal Gardens, this must-see place is ideal for family vacationers, honeymoon couples, and even for solo travellers seeking peace.

Dal Lake is also one of the best locations in Kashmir for film shooting as it offers some incredible vistas of lofty rolling hills, the distant snow-capped mountains, shikaras cruising quietly and the houseboat standing still with the perfect poise.

The canopied Shikaras sailing on the lake are one of the major attractions of Dal Lake. The houseboats on the lake are also the top attraction as the best accommodation option in Srinagar to the tourists.

Along with being a popular tourist attraction for nature lovers, Dal Lake even invites the fishing enthusiast with its plethora of fishes along with Carp. In addition to this, the floating vegetable and flower market is a major place to see.

Major Highlight of Dal lake Tour

Shikara rides,
houseboat stay,
and floating vegetable market.

name: Devrshi Rathore
review_text:
The earliest records, such as Kalhanas Rajatarangini, mentions the Sanskrit name shri-nagara which have been interpreted distinctively by scholars in two ways: one being surya-nagar, meaning City of the City of Sun and other being The city of Shri (shrii), the Hindu goddess of wealth.The city is located on both the sides of the Jhelum River, which is called Vyath in Kashmir. The river passes through the city and meanders through the valley, moving onward and deepening in the Wular Lake. The city is known for its nine old bridges, connecting the two parts of the city.

There are a number of lakes and swamps in and around the city. These include the Dal, the Nigeen, the Anchar, Khushal Sar, Gil Sar and Hokersar.

Hokersar is a wetland situated near Srinagar. Thousands of migratory birds come to Hokersar from Siberia and other regions in the winter season. Migratory birds from Siberia and Central Asia use wetlands in Kashmir as their transitory camps between September and October and again around spring. These wetlands play a vital role in sustaining a large population of wintering, staging and breeding birds.

Hokersar is 14 km (8.7 mi) north of Srinagar, and is a world class wetland spread over 13.75 km2 (5.31 sq mi) including lake and marshy area. It is the most accessible and well-known of Kashmirs wetlands which include Hygam, Shalibug and Mirgund. A record number of migratory birds have visited Hokersar in recent years.[37]

Road

The city is served by many highways, including National Highway 1A and National Highway 1D.[58]

Air

Srinagar International Airport has regular domestic flights to Leh, Jammu, Chandigarh, Delhi and Mumbai and occasional international flights. An expanded terminal capable of handling both domestic and international flights was inaugurated on 14 February 2009 with Air India Express flights to Dubai. Hajj flights also operate from this airport to Saudi Arabia.[59]

Rail

Main articles: Srinagar railway station and Srinagar Metro

Srinagar is a station on the 119 km (74 mi) long Banihal-Baramulla line that started in October 2009 and connects Baramulla to Srinagar, Anantnag and Qazigund. The railway track also connects to Banihal across the Pir Panjal mountains through a newly constructed 11 km long Banihal tunnel, and subsequently to the Indian railway network after a few years. It takes approximately 9 minutes and 30 seconds for a train to cross the tunnel. It is the longest rail tunnel in India. This railway system, proposed in 2001, is not expected to connect the Indian railway network until 2017 at the earliest, with a cost overrun of 55 billion INR.[60] The train also runs during heavy snow.

There are proposals to develop a metro system in the city.[61] The feasibility report for the Srinagar Metro is planned to be carried out by Delhi Metro Rail Corporation.[62]

name: Shiva Chaudhary (Shivaji)
review_text:
Dal Sarovar or Dal Sarovar is a famous lake located in Srinagar, Kashmir. Spread over an area of   12 square kilometers, the lake is surrounded by hills on three sides.

It is the second largest lake in the state of Jammu and Kashmir. In this, water comes from sources. At the same time many lakes of Kashmir valley come and join in this. It has four major reservoirs: Gagaribal, Lokut Dal, Bod Dal and Nagin. Ruplank Island is located in the middle of Lokut Dal and Sonalank Island is located in the middle of Bod Dal reservoir. It is named after one of the most beautiful lakes in India. The beauty of Dal Sarovar looks unparalleled from the nearby Mughal Vatika. It is not uncommon for a tourist to come to Jammu and Kashmir and visit Dal Sarovar. [1]

The main attraction of Dal Sarovar is the hunting or houseboat. Passengers can enjoy the lake by staying in these houseboats. Nehru Park, Kanutur Khana, Charchinari Islands and Hazrat Bal can also be visited. Extra stores are also available for hunting and a variety of items can be purchased on the hunt. A variety of vegetation enhances the beauty of Dal Sarovar. The lotus flower, the lily flowing in the water, adds four moons to the beauty of the lake. A variety of recreational facilities for hikers such as kayaking, canoeing, water surfing and fishing are available here. Apart from tourism, Dal Sarovar is mainly used for fishing.

name: Aaqib
review_text: Dal Lake is a top tourist destination in Srinagar and is the second largest lake in the state of Jammu & Kashmir. Due to its beauty and serenity, it is known as the "Jewel in the Crown" of Kashmir. It is spread over 18-22 km sq and offers various tourist destinations, shops and markets.

name: Anil Dobriyal
review_text: Nyc

name: Nadeem Parry
review_text:
Dal is a warm monomictic lake.The lake is located within a catchment area covering 316 square kilometres (122 sq mi) in the Zabarwan mountain valley.
Multiple theories explaining the origin of this lake have been formulated. One version is that it is the remnants of a post-glacial lake, which has undergone drastic changes in size over the years and the other theory is that it is of fluvial origin from an old flood spill channel or ox-bows of the Jhelum river.
The lake is an important source for commercial operations in fishing and water plant harvesting.
Inflow Channel Telbal Nallah from Marsar lake.
Outflow is regulated by two channels Dal Gate and Nalla Amir.
The shore line of the lake, about 15.5 kilometres (9.6 mi), is encompassed by a boulevard lined with Mughal era gardens, parks, houseboats and hotels.
Scenic views of the lake can be witnessed from the shore line Mughal gardens, such as Shalimar Bagh and Nishat Bagh built during the reign of Jahangir.
During the Mughal period, the Mughal rulers of India designated Kashmir, Srinagar in particular, as their summer resort. They developed the precincts of the Dal in Srinagar with sprawling Mughal-type gardens and pavilions as pleasure resorts to enjoy the salubrious cool climate.
The ecosystem of Dal is ecologically rich in macrophytes, submerged macrophytes, floating macrophytes and phytoplankton. Macrophyte flora recorded in the lakes aquatic and marshland environment consists of 117 species, belonging to 69 genera and 42 families. The lake is noted in particular for its Nelumbo nucifera (lotus flowers) which bloom in July and August

name: Ms Map
review_text:
Dal Lake is in Srinagar. It is second largest lake in J&K. Dal Lake is also called as Lake of Flowers, Jewel in the crown of Kashmir or Srinagars Jewel. There are two islands also as Sona Lank and Rupa Lank (or Char Chinar)..

A lake carries you into recesses of feeling otherwise impenetrable
~ William Wordsworth

In every season, you are going to experience something different in Dal Lake but BEAUTIFULLY DIFFERENT i.e., frozen Dal, Dal Lake covered with Lotus, Sunset views, the calmness, the islands, the floating markets and what not.. then there are Shikara rides and there are houseboats to stay... So, pay a visit to our beautiful Dal Lake once in your lifetime..!!

There are floating markets that you can visit, buy local kashmir shawls or pherans for your loved ones, buy fruits vegetables also and even have hot tea and snacks while sitting in the shikara. An out of the world experience!

review_text: Dal lake is a must visit if you are in srinagar. It has amazing view. Sikara ride is a must to do however be careful while selecting the one. Most sikara owners will try to cheat you by asking for very high price and short ride only. There will be many of them who will surround you and chase you making you irritated. They will force you to visit floating market as they get commission. Real beauty of Dal lake is around Char minar where most sikara owners will not take you because its far and there is market for them to get commission. Dal lake has almost 30 ghats and 3 jetteys, board sikara only after gate 15 so as to get better view of Dal Lake and insist to take you to Open Dal Lake and Char minar. Pay Rs. 200 to 300 for 2 hour ride which is reasonable price.

review_text:
We arrived in Srinagar at dawn after riding in a jeep for 12 hours from Leh.
I woke up the next day and planned to take my time to see the village, but after hearing the news of the gunfight a few hours ago, I immediately booked a flight to Amritsar as soon as I arrived...
I woke up with a sigh and got ready to board the plane, but right in front of my accommodation was Dal lake, which is famous for houseboats, so I took a 10-minute boat ride and completed my first and last trip in Srinagar.

The snowy mountains seen from the clear lake are really... good.
