review_text:
Dal is a Lake in Srinagar, the summer capital of Jammu & Kashmir. The lake covers an area of twenty two square kilometres and is a great spot for tourism. We went there on 25th of December and stayed in the Houseboat for that night. Shikara(Small boats) was the only agent of communication between our Houseboat and the mainland.
The Houseboat was beautifully decorated with wooden decorations in Kasmiri style. There were bukharis (Fire place)in all of our rooms to keep the room heated.Next morning, the scenic beauty of the Dal Lake was awesome from the Houseboat. The quality of the food was also very good. Thus,we had a very good experience in the Houseboat.

name: Numaan Riyaz
review_text:
Dal Lake in Srinagar has a picture-perfect spot that travellers to Srinagar cannot miss. Surrounded by majestic mountains on one side, the lake is a center of attraction for the travelers arriving to this place called, paradise on earth.

Most tourism-oriented activites on the lake happen near the Dal Gate. You can take a shikara ride on colourful high-backed seats, buy flowers from floating shops, get yourself clicked in kitschy Kashmiri dresses, visit Nehru Park Island and Char Chinar Island, see the floating vegetable market at dawn, visit Hazratbal, and traverse the smaller and quieter Nagin Lake and the old Pandit quarter of Rainawari.

The houseboats anchored on the Dal are often huge and spacious. Over the years, houseboats grew in number with many flaunting new designs, comforts and outlook. If you can accommodate yourself in one of these you will feel yourself closer to the heritage and culture of Kashmir.

name: Tahir Ahmad
review_text:
Dal is a lake in Srinagar, the summer capital of Jammu and Kashmir, India. It is an urban lake, which is the second largest in the union territory of Jammu and Kashmir. It is integral to tourism and recreation in Kashmir and is named the Lake of Flowers Jewel in the crown of Kashmir or Srinagars Jewel.The lake is also an important source for commercial operations in fishing and water plant harvesting.

Max. length 7.44 km (4.62 mi)
Max. width 3.5 km (2.2 mi)
Surface area 18-22 square kms (6.9-8.5 sq mi)
Average depth 1.42 metres (4.7 ft)
Max. depth 6 m (20 ft)

name: BHAT IRSHAD
review_text:
Over 15km around, Dal Lake is Srinagars jewel, a vast sheet of water reflecting the carved wooden balconies of the houseboats and the misty peaks of the Pir Panjal mountains. Flotillas of gaily painted shikaras (gondola-like taxi boats) skiff around the lake, transporting goods to market, children to school and travellers to delightful houseboats inspired by originals from the Raj era.
If you get up early, you can paddle out to see the floating flower and vegetable market: a colourful spectacle, but one where you can expect plenty of attention from souvenir vendors.
There are three islands in the lake separated by the causeways that in itself is a major attraction. Houseboats with swimming facilities are allowed during summer and can be very refreshing. There are other interesting places to visit near Dal Lake, in particular, the pleasant Mughal gardens, ancient temple of Shankaracharya, the Island of Char Chinar, Nagin Lake, Chashme Shahi, Hazratbal Shrine, and Mazar-e-Shura Cemetery.

One of the most incredible places in India, Kashmir known for its enthralling beauty and is rightly nicknamed as the 'Heaven on Earth'. With its Picturesque lakes, striking fruit orchards, verdant meadows surrounded with thick woods of pines and deodars, lush green gardens teeming with vibrant flowers and captivating valleys enclosed with snow-covered peaks of Himalayan and Pir-Panjal ranges - Kashmir seems to have directly made its way out from a picture postcard. From enjoying a heavenly ' ride' the pristine 'Dal Lake strolling through the beautifully manicured 'Mughal Gardens', soaking in the untouched pastoral beauty of 'Betaab' and 'Aru' valleys, paying your homage to 'Amarnath ji' standing amidst the ethereal natural beauty of the tiny hamlet of 'Chandanwari'

name: Prashant Kumar
review_text: The jewel in the crown of Kashmir," as you might now guess, is the place to see in Kashmir valley. At Dal Lake, the tuk-tuk life of India's frenetic cities is traded for slow cruises along the water in traditional wooden shikaras (similar to a canoe). Fishermen use these to paddle their way to and from ornate houseboats lining the shore and the lake's famous floating market to peddle just-picked fruit and vegetables or flowers. Another landmark is the Shalimar Bagh, on the lake's right bank, which is lauded as the finest Mughal garden in all of India.

review_text:
The beauty of dal lake cannot described in words. It is a main tourist attraction of Srinagar city. The view of the lake is breathtaking. It is filled with tourists particularly in summer and spring.

The houseboats and shikaras are a main focus of the lake. The Shikara ride is one of a kind. You can view the lake from inside in shikaras. The houseboats are a luxurious place to live for toruists in the Dal Lake.

But now a days, due to encroachment of the lake its span is continuously decreasing. Another problem is the dirt and affluent dumped in the Dal Lake which pollutes the Dal and makes it filthy and smelly.

I request the locals and the visitors to kindly make efforts to keep the Dal clean. Do not throw wrappers and waste in the Dal. Use roadside dustbins!

review_text: Talking about Srinagar Hill Station and forgetting to mention Dal Lake it would be completely inappropriate. Dal Lake is a beautiful and delightful tourist destination in Srinagar. The lake is well known for the Shikara, a wooden boat, and a houseboat. From the houseboat, there is a lovely outing to Dal Lake, while riding from Shikara to Dal Lake and the houseboat. Houseboats offer a panoramic view of Dal Lake as well as panoramic views of the mountains near the lake. The lake market is the main attraction for shopping and there are many shops in the middle of the lake. Handmade earrings, wooden artwork, and saffron can be found here. It is my favorite place in Srinagar.

Kashmer is heaven of india.. it is just loving place.. and dal lake is one of its beauty

We stayed on the ALPS Houseboat on Dal lake, during our brief stay in Srinagar. The lake is as beautiful as ever. The top layer was frozen in the morning and it was one of an experience to ride the shikara moving through the frozen..
Serene and peaceful.Natural beauty with a majestic view. A great boat ride to enjoy the daily life of local people

we went to take the shikara ride. The shikara we took was "PATLOO PALACE" rowed by two cute old gentlemen. The dal lake, the surrounding mountains gave a spectacular view of the lake. It felt like we are floating in heaven. There are totally 6points in dal lake and they asked us 2500, but we managed to bargain it to 2000. There is no time limit. The fun part was that while you are tanking the shikara ride, there will be many different Shikaras and salesmen who will approach you and try to sell their handicrafts. please bargain the price with them...!! You can also get down and shop or eat on the Shikaras which are fixed there, also known as the houseboats. There is a Nehru garden in the middle of the lake, which is free entry. It's just a small garden .. get down take pics, eat in the restaurant and that's it.

--Niloy Mahata

name: Rizwan Farooq
review_text:
Dal Lake located right in the middle of Sir Yangar, the capital of Occupied Kashmir, is the mirror of Kashmir and its transparent water reflects all the wonders of Kashmir.

Initially, the place of Dal was a waterless plain and it is called Vatial Murg. Later, the lake was formed by the springs and streams that came down from the mountains and gradually it took the form of a large and beautiful lake, which is about 5 miles in length and 2.5 miles in width. The depth of this lake, located in the north-west of Srinagar, will be around 15 lakh feet. In Badi-Nazar, it has divided Srinagar into two parts. But at a short distance it also divides itself into two parts. One part is called Chota Dal and the other part is called Big Dal.

Its depth continues to decrease at various places. Syed Mahmood Azad has written while describing the auspicious environment of this lake and its wonderful conditions:
The charm created by the small farms floating on the water on the banks of Jheel Dal is beyond human reach. In these fields, the boatmen here, who are called Hanji in Kashmiri language, cultivate various vegetables. The scene of these fields dancing on Lake Dal looks just like the nature artist himself has landed in the lake and started dancing. When the kadam leaves sway from the bamboo in these floating fields, their reflection is seen in the dal water just like the green fairies dancing on the surface of the water, but all this is a refreshing and soulful scene. Spring festivals are auspicious because in winter, when the frozen waves rise from Lake Dal, no one goes near it.

review_text:
Beautiful place in India. Dal is a lake in Srinagar. The urban lake, which is the second largest in the union territory, is integral to tourism and recreation in Kashmir and is named the  Lake of Flowers,Jewel in the crown of Kashmir or Srinagars JewelThe lake is also an important source for commercial operations in fishing and water plant harvesting.
The shore line of the lake, about 15.5 kilometres (9.6 mi), is encompassed by a boulevard lined with Mughal era gardens, parks, houseboats and hotels. Scenic views of the lake can be witnessed from the shore line Mughal gardens, such as Shalimar Bagh and Nishat Bagh built during the reign of Mughal Emperor Jahangir and from houseboats cruising along the lake in the colourful shikaras.The ecosystem of Dal is ecologically rich in macrophytes, submerged macrophytes, floating macrophytes and phytoplankton. Macrophyte flora recorded in the lakes aquatic and marshland environment consists of 117 species, belonging to 69 genera and 42 families.

It covers an area of 18 square kilometres and is part of a natural wetland including its floating gardens.

The floating gardens, known as "Raad" in Kashmiri, blossom with lotus flowers during July and August.

The wetland is divided by causeways into four basins; Gagribal, Lokut Dal, Bod Dal and Nagin. Lokut-dal and Bod-dal each have an island in the centre, known as Rup Lank (or Char Chinari) and Sona Lank respectively.

The houseboats (Shikaras) are closely associated with Dal Lake which provide accommodation to tourists in Srinagar.

name: Karthik
review_text:
Jammu & Kashmir is the most beautiful state of the whole Indian sub continent and the city of Srinagar is famously known as the paradise of the east. The city of Srinagar is actually the summer capital of the state of Jammu & Kashmir. The Srinagar is a valley drained by the Jhelum River, a tributary of the Indus River. The valley amidst the high and snowy mountain, filled with lush green pasture is truly paradise like. At the centre of Srinagar city lies the most beautiful fresh water lake of the whole India, the Dal Lake. It is without any doubt, the main attraction of Srinagar and the hotspot of Jammu & Kashmir Tourism.

The Dal Lake is a fresh water lake in the catchment of Jhelum and on its banks the main city has flourished. The water of the lake is very clear and in reality it is a segregation of three lakes joined by maze level intricate water channels. The Dal Lake is very beautiful and it is very picturesque with a back drop of high White Mountains.

The main attraction of the Dal Lake is the Char Chinar and the floating vegetation. Char Chinar is a lake island ate the centre housing very old four chinar trees. The floating vegetation serves both beauty and ecological purposes for the lake. The whole tourism industry of Srinagar is built in the lake.

The houseboats are best accommodation for the travelers, the floating gardens are best beautification for the trips and roaming the lake on elegant & aristocratic Shikaras is just the epitome of Srinagar visit for the tourists. Apart from these the market place on the lake is also a great tourist magnate and to make Dal Lake further engaging, the tourist will be offered to taste the mouth-watering cuisines of local delicacy.

name: Dipayan Mukherjee
review_text:
Dal is the urban lake, which is the second largest in the union territory, is integral to tourism and recreation in Kashmir and is named the  Lake of Flowers, Jewel in the crown of Kashmir or Srinagars Jewel.The lake is also an important source for commercial operations in fishing and water plant harvesting.
The shore line of the lake, about 15.5 kilometres, is encompassed by a boulevard lined with Mughal era gardens, parks, houseboats and hotels. Scenic views of the lake can be witnessed from the shore line Mughal gardens, and from houseboats cruising along the lake in the colourful shikaras.During the winter season, the temperature sometimes reaches 11 degC (12 degF), freezing the lake.
The lake covers an area of 18 square kilometres and is part of a natural wetland which covers 21.1 square kilometres , including its floating gardens. The floating gardens, known as Rad in Kashmiri, blossom with lotus flowers during July and August. The wetland is divided by causeways into four basins; Gagribal, Lokut Dal, Bod Dal and Nigeen (although Nigeen is also considered as an independent lake). Lokut-dal and Bod-dal each have an island in the centre, known as Rup Lank (or Char Chinari) and Sona Lank respectively.
Basically its a very beautiful place surrounded with serenity of nature. The amazing fact is that, you get to see different senery of nature in each season. In winter its freezes and take a form of cold and white vibe. In spring its becomes warm and welcoming. In summer you will feel soothing peace. And Autumn will make you hollow and melancholy.

Most beautiful place in the world. ....ye nahi dekha to kya dekha

Dal Lake Located in Srinagar city, which is 6.4 km long and 4km wide, and within its periphery, four enormous expanses of water - Lokut Dal, Bod Dal, Gagribal and Nagin. Hence, Dal Lake is not a flat, continuous mass of water, but an intricate maze of waterways, making for a spectacular sight and an even more enchanting locale to explore.To the delight of the visitors they can enjoy fascinating rides on traditional Kashmiri Houseboats and Shikaras. The Shikara ride can be an hour-long sightseeing session of the Dal a shopping-by-shikara expedition to handicraft shops within the lake area; or a whole-day trip featuring visits to major landmarks in Srinagar.

This beautiful lake of Kashmir valley is revered not only for its spectacular beauty, but also for its vibrancy, because within its periphery, the lake sustains a unique life, unmatched elsewhere. The Houseboat and Shikhara communities have lived for ages on the Dal, and have created such a complete infrastructure that they do not need to step on land for their day-to-day sustenance.

name: Jashu Kumar
review_text:
Back in April end this year i travelled to Kashmir. Indeed a heaven. It was my first trip to Kashmir . We were 3 friends & below is our itinerary with per person cost.

Day1: Delhi- Chandigarh by Janshatabdi (Rs.150)
Chandigarh- Jammu by Zimindara Ac sleeper bus (Rs.600)

Day2: Early morning bus from Jammu to Banihal from bus stand (Rs.120)
Banihal to Srinagar by Passenger train (Rs.20). Seats are very comfortable in this train.
Taj Mahal Houseboat check-in (Rs.400)
Main road to Houseboat by Shikara & sunset ride (Rs.300)
Explored Srinagar a little during sunset

Day3: Early morning Srinagar to Sonamarg by bus (Rs.100)
Hotel Barzman check-in (Rs.600)
Thajiwas Glacier trek
Zojila visit & back (FREE , A couple was going there in their own car so we requested them to take us with them, they happily agreed)
Night walk in Sonamarg with full moon & so many stars 

Day4: Early morning Sonamarg to Srinagar by taxi from taxi stand (Rs.120)
Srinagar to Banihal by Passenger train (Rs.20)
Banihal to Jammu by shared taxi (Rs.200)
Jammu to Delhi by Duronto Express 3AC (Rs.1200).

Day5: Reached Delhi at 5 a.m.

Total cost is approx 4000 Rs.
Plus 2000 Rs. for food & other little expenses.

So this is how you visit Kashmir under 6k .

LocationSrinagar, Jammu and Kashmir, IndiaCoordinates34deg07'N 74deg52'ELake typeWarm monomicticPrimary inflowsInflow Channel Telbal Nallah from Marsar lake 291.9 million cubic metresPrimary outflowsRegulated, two channels (Dal Gate and Nalla Amir) - 275.6 million cubic metresCatchment area316 square kilometres (122 sq mi)Basin countriesIndiaMax. length7.44 km (4.62 mi)Max. width3.5 km (2.2 mi)Surface area18-22 square kilometres (6.9-8.5 sq mi)Average depth1.42 metres (4.7 ft)Max. depth6 m (20 ft)Water volume983 million cubic metres (34.7x109 cu ft)Residence time22.16 daysShore length115.5 km (9.6 mi)Surface elevation1,583 m (5,194 ft)FrozenDuring severe winterIslandsTwo (Sona Lank and Rupa Lank (or Char Chinar))SettlementsHazratbal, Srinagar1 Shore length is not a well-defined measure.

The shore line of the lake, about 15.5 kilometres (9.6 mi), is encompassed by a boulevard lined with Mughal era gardens, parks, houseboats and hotels. Scenic views of the lake can be witnessed from the shore line Mughal gardens, such as Shalimar Bagh and Nishat Bagh built during the reign of MughalEmperor Jahangir[7] and from houseboats cruising along the lake in the colourful shikaras.[8] During the winter season, the temperature sometimes reaches 11 degC (12 degF), freezing the lake.[6][9]

The lake covers an area of 18 square kilometres (6.9 sq mi) and is part of a natural wetland which covers 21.1 square kilometres (8.1 sq mi), including its floating gardens. The floating gardens, known as Rad in Kashmiri, blossom with lotus flowers during July and August. The wetland is divided by causewaysinto four basins; Gagribal, Lokut Dal, Bod Daland Nigeen (although Nigeen is also considered as an independent lake). Lokut-dal and Bod-dal each have an island in the centre, known as Rup Lank (or Char Chinari) and Sona Lank respectively.[9][10]

At present, the Dal and its Mughal gardens, Shalimar Bagh and the Nishat Bagh on its periphery are undergoing intensive restoration measures to fully address the serious eutrophication problems experienced by the lake. Massive investments of approximately US$275 million ( 11 billion) are being made by the Government of India to restore the lake to its original splendour.[6][9][10][11

review_text:
Had been to this beautiful lake in Srinagar a long back ago. This lake is a main tourist attraction in Srinagar.
This lake attracts a lot of Indian & foreign tourists every year. Also, this lake has a lot of houseboats, shops, a hotel on an artificial island etc. There are unique type of boats known as a Shikara takes tourists around the lake. There are local photographers who asks tourists to wear local costumes and get their photos clicked along with it. Also, this lake is a floating market where local vendors trade with each other and sell their merchandise to the customers. However, this lake gets dirty due to these local vendors as well as tourists. From this lake, one can see a fortress, Zabarwan mountain range as well as Shankarcharya Temple.
This serene and calm lake is ideal for families, couples as well as friends. A Shikara boat ride on this lake should not be missed while in Srinagar.

name: Ultimate Travellers
review_text:
Dal is a lake in Srinagar, the summer capital of Jammu and Kashmir, India. The urban lake, which is the second largest in the union territory, is integral to tourism and recreation in Kashmir and is named the  Lake of Flowers ,Jewel in the crown of Kashmiror Srinagars JewelThe lake is also an important source for commercial operations in fishing and water plant harvesting.The shore line of the lake, about 15.5 kilometres 9.6 mi, is encompassed by a boulevard lined with Mughal era gardens, parks, houseboats and hotels. Scenic views of the lake can be witnessed from the shore line Mughal gardens, such as Shalimar Bagh and Nishat Bagh built during the reign of MughalEmperor Jahangirand from houseboats cruising along the lake in the colourful shikaras.During the winter season, the temperature sometimes reaches 11 degC 12 degF, freezing the lake.
The lake covers an area of 18 square kilometres 6.9 sq mi and is part of a natural wetland which covers 21.1 square kilometres 8.1 sq mi, including its floating gardens. The floating gardens, known as Rad in Kashmiri, blossom with lotus flowers during July and August. The wetland is divided by causewaysinto four basins; Gagribal, Lokut Dal, Bod Daland Nigeen although Nigeen is also considered as an independent lake. Lokut-dal and Bod-dal each have an island in the centre, known as Rup Lank or Char Chinari and Sona Lank respectively.
At present, the Dal and its Mughal gardens, Shalimar Bagh and the Nishat Bagh on its periphery are undergoing intensive restoration measures to fully address the serious eutrophication problems experienced by the lake. Massive investments of approximately US$275 million  11 billion are being made by the Government of India to restore the lake to its original splendour.Dal is mentioned as Mahasarit (Sanskrti-mhaasrit) in ancient Sanskrit texts. Ancient history records mention that a village named Isabar to the east of Dal was the residence of goddess Durga.This place was known as Sureshwari on the bank of the lake, which was sourced by a spring called the Satadhara.
During the Mughal period, the Mughal rulers of India designated Kashmir, Srinagar in particular, as their summer resort. They developed the precincts of the Dal in Srinagar with sprawling Mughal-type gardens and pavilions as pleasure resorts to enjoy the salubrious cool climate.After the death of Aurangzeb in 1707, which led to the disintegration of the Mughal Empire,Pashtun tribes in the area around the lake and city increased, and the Afghan Durrani Empireruled the city for several decades.In 1814 a significant part of the Kashmir valley, including Srinagar, was annexed from the Afghans by Raja Ranjit Singh to his kingdom, and the Sikhs grew in influence in the region for 27 years.During the Dogra Raj, Srinagar became the capital of Dogra dynasty, attracted by the cool climate of the Kashmir valley, amidst the back drop of the majestic snow covered Himalayan ranges. The lake precincts experience temperatures in the range of 1-11 degC 34-52 degF during winter and 12-30 degC 54-86 degF during the summer season. The lake freezes when temperatures drop to about 11 degC 12 degF during severe winter.Although the Dogra Maharaja of Kashmir restricted the building of houses in the valley, the British circumvented this rule by commissioning lavish houseboats to be built on the Dal. The houseboats have been referred to as, each one a little piece of England afloat on Dal.
After the independence of India, the Kashmiri Hanji people have built, owned and maintained these houseboats, cultivating floating gardens and producing commodities for the market, making them the centre of their livelihoods. The houseboats, closely associated with Dal also provide accommodation in Srinagar. Following the Mughal, Afghan, Sikh and Dogra rule, the place has earned the epithet, Jewel in the crown of Kashmir.

review_text:
Who wouldnt love this serene place? Just a transparent blanket of clean water overlooking mountains of both tall and somewhat short sizes. Sure, looking down at the lake is scary because of the abundance of seaweed but the cleanliness fills one with piece. The people did well maintaining this place, barely any littering is seen. Besides the summer, the mountains are snow capped.

On various sides of the lake lies houseboats, a very unique aspect of the lake. They are floating hotels, offering an unreal experience for the tourists, which have varying architecture and most appearing royal like the Mughal times. The little boats (shikara as called by the locals) are quiant little things which looks like a smaller version of the houseboats.

During the winter, of course, the lake freezes over. Perhaps offering another surreal experience.

review_text:
Dal Lake is a lake in the city of Srinagar in the state of Kashmir. It is the second largest lake in the state and is considered one of its most important tourism and entertainment destinations. It is called "the jewel in the crown of Kashmir" or "the jewel of Srinagar". The lake is also an important commercial source for fishing and harvesting aquatic plants.

Dal lake



Coordinates34deg07'00''N74deg52'00''E Area20 square kilometers Length7.44 km Source edit - edit 

The lakes shoreline is located on an area of   about 15.5 kilometers (9.6 mi) and includes Mughal-era gardens, houseboats, and a number of hotels. The lake offers stunning views, so you can see a number of nearby villages and boats sailing along the lake in its attractive colors. During the winter season, temperatures drop sometimes to -11 degrees Celsius and the lake freezes.

Covering an area of   18 km2 (6.9 sq mi), Dal Lake is part of the 21.1 km2 (8.1 sq mi) natural water park that includes floating gardens, known as radh in Kashmir and covered during the months of July and August with lotus blossoms. The water areas are divided through bridges into four basins. They are Lokot Dal, Gagripal, Budh Dal and Naagin. The Lokot Dal and Bud Dal basins have islands in their center called "Rup Lank" and "Sona Lank" respectively.

Currently, Dal Lake and the Mughal Gardens adjacent to it are undergoing intensive measures to address the serious problems of eutrophication that the lake suffers from, and a huge investment of about US$ 275 million is currently being made by the Indian government to restore the lake to its original splendor.

name: vishal barmeru
review_text:
Crystal clear sheet of water with a magnificent reflection of the azure sky and the mystique Pir Panjal range in the background- this picture perfect view is a delight for the eyes. This is Dal Lake- the jewel of Kashmir. Its magnificent beauty and captivating aura have enchanted visitors from ages.
Are you interested in knowing more about this lake? Here are a few quick facts to give you a sneak-peek:
1. Dal lake is not just one lake but, it is a union of three lakes. It is divided into two more parts, the Lokut and Bod Dal. This is the second largest lake in Jammu and Kashmir and receives its water supply from the mountain lake Mar Sar. When visiting the Dal lake, you'll find it an enchanting maze consisting of intricate waterways, numerous channels, and floating islands. Dal Lake is also popular for fishing activities and is also used for harvesting water plants.

The line of the lake is hemmed by beautiful flower gardens, hotels, and parks. The gardens around it were built in the pre-independence era. The most famous of them is the Shalimar Bagh. You can also enjoy a great view of the Dal Lake from Shalimar Bagh. During winter, when the temperature dips down to -11 degree celcius, the lake freezes. You can enjoy skiing on the frozen surface of the Dal lake.

3. This lake is spread over an area of 18 square kilometers and also covers the area of a wetland of around 21.1 square kilometers. This wetland includes all the floating gardens and water plantation. If you visit Dal lake during the month of July, you will find these floating gardens covered in flowers of different hues. There is abundance of vegetation all across the lake. You will find trees like Pine, Cupressus, Gerardiana, Celtis to name a few.

4. In ancient scriptures, Dal lake is considered as Mahasarit. According to the scriptures, there was a village named Isabar in the eastern part of the lake and was a residence of Goddess Durga.

5. The Mughals took great care in designing the state of Kashmir. Since Srinagar was frequented by people due to its scenic beauty, the Mughals designed lakes and adjoining gardens for making the place more picturesque. Dal lake was one of them.

name: Razwon Khan
review_text: Dal lake of Kashmir is one of the most beautiful and picturesque lakes in India.The sparkling quiet waters of Dal surrounded by snow-capped mountains on its three sides, undoubtedly mark it as one of the most beautiful lakes of India. Numerous houseboats line the lake, providing their guests with serene atmosphere and picturesque surroundings. The Shikaras provide ferry rides to and from the banks of the lake to the houseboats.

name: RAVI KOUL
review_text: Dal Lake is an absolute enigma, a one off. Located within the city of Srinagar its an incredible jewel of a lake, with intricately carved wooden houseboats lined up along the Boulevard side and beyond, and decorated canoes called shikaras which ply the lake taking people to and from the houseboats or just around the lake and backwaters for a unique sightseeing experience. BUT, despite the beautiful mountain backdrop and serene waters topped with lilies and over flown by brightly coloured kingfishers this is where the idyll ends. To walk along the Boulevard is to subject yourself to a continuous wave of hassle and disturbance. The shikara touts, tuk tuk drivers and houseboat owners are literally wall to wall along the Boulevard and it is a constant plague of harassment rather than a pleasant walk. Ive learned to just walk by each ghat (shikara mooring station where you get transport to and from your houseboat if youre brave (or mad!) enough to risk putting yourself through a stay on one of these floating white elephants) with my hand up saying no, no, no before they get a chance to open their mouths because Ive become tired of smiling and being nice to them all. Its an absolute den of creepiness totally absorbed by how much money they can extract from you, and it isnt a pleasant experience at all. The houseboats themselves? Well, theyre a whole other story with issues of their own! Ive given Dal Lake an average rating rather than lower because it IS outstandingly beautiful beyond the people who are ruining and exploiting it. Its worth a visit to see a unique place but 2 days is enough! Very sad that an incredible place can be so destroyed by the local peoples greedy attitudes...

review_text:
Dal lake : the epitome of Kashmiri vacation !!!

Kashmir / Srinagar has always remained the "jannat" or heaven for an average Indian. The beautiful locations, cool climates varied colours of nature. You have everything for a romantic gateway. Add Dal lake to it and you have a perfect spot.
Dal lake is collections of many basins and covers an area of roughly 20 Sqr kms. It has everything: House boats , floating markets, park , restaurants, agriculture "fields". You think of it and you have it. Including defence base.
You have all the items on sale. So , you may get fresh fruit salad or Maggi. You may decide to order a walnut table for your home or you surprise your partner with a kashmiri dress. Choices are unlimited.
The ancient Shankaracharya temple stands as a guardian and a sentinel to this lake and area around this.
During summers , one can enjoy the salubrious climate boat ride. During winter , this is definitely chilly. In extreme season , the lake also freezes. I have met people who claim that they have sat on the frozen lake or played cricket.
In any case , trip to Srinagar can never be complete without Dal lake.

name: Jabir Islam
review_text:
The shore line of the lake, is about 15.5 kilometres (9.6 mi), is encompassed by a boulevard lined with Mughal era gardens, parks, houseboats and hotels. Scenic views of the lake can be witnessed from the shore line Mughal gardens, such as Shalimar Bagh and Nishat Bagh built during the reign of Mughal Emperor Jahangir[6] and from houseboats cruising along the lake in the colourful shikaras.[7]During the winter season, the temperature sometimes reaches 11 degC (12 degF), freezing the lake.[5][8]

The lake covers an area of 18 square kilometres (6.9 sq mi) and is part of a natural wetland which covers 21.1 square kilometres (8.1 sq mi), including its floating gardens. The floating gardens, known as Rad in Kashmiri, blossom with lotus flowers during July and August. The wetland is divided by causeways into four basins; Gagribal, Lokut Dal, Bod Dal and Nigeen (although Nigeen is also considered as an independent lake). Lokut-dal and Bod-dal each have an island in the centre, known as Rup Lank (or Char Chinari) and Sona Lankrespectively.[8][9]

At present, the Dal and its Mughal gardens, Shalimar Bagh and the Nishat Bagh on its periphery are undergoing intensive restoration measures to fully address the serious eutrophication problems experienced by the lake. Massive investments of approximately US$275 million ( 11 billion) are being made by the Government of India to restore the lake to its original splendour.

name: zyda azyan
review_text:
I had the most amazing and incredible time on the houseboat at Lake Dal, Srinagar. The lake is also known as the jewel in the Crown of Kashmir or the Jewel of Srinagar.
The shoreline is 15.5 km long that covers a 21.1sqkm of natural wetlands. The lake is surrounded by gardens, greenery and houseboats. The mode of transport from land to the houseboats via the colorful shikaras.
I stayed for two nights at the houseboat, complete with a butler and a cook. It was not a nice experience staying at the houseboat as the owner kept pestering me to buy leather bags from his son, to the point of harrasing me.
But I want to focus on the beautiful lake. The water is clear and turquiose. The colorful shikaras adds substance to the whole landscape.
I enjoyed the one-hour shikara ride very much and bought a silver crowned-precious stone ring.
We stopped at some of the floating shops for shawls and fridge magnets.
I love it as it is a different kind of shopping experience, parking the shikara, instead of a car.
I love the smooth and peaceful ride in the shikara, except for the occasional disturbance from the floating traders. Once, they are ignored, the ride was wonderful.
Once back at the Dock to the houseboat, I just stood and watch the lake, the birds, the shikaras and the absolute beauty at the Lake Dal. It was totally mesmerising as the lake is kept clear and clean. I suppose it is a concerted efforts from the authorities as well as the people living at the lake.
I had an incredibly wonderful time at the Lake Dal, Srinagar.

name: Mumtaz Lone
review_text:
The urban lake, which is the second largest in the state, is integral to tourism and recreation in Kashmir and is named the Jewel in the crown of Kashmir or Srinagars Jewel.The lake is also an important source for commercial operations in fishing and water plant harvesting.
Houseboats
The largest group of houseboats lies along the western edge of the lake near the lakeside boulevard, towards Dal gate. They are lined in looping rows and around small islands. Several hotels can also be found on flat islands in the lake. Beyond the houseboats to the northwest are the floating gardens.

Attractions Around Dal Lake
There are three islands in the lake; three real islands anyway, there are other sorts of islands joined by causeways. Around the lake are many of Srinagars most interesting sights, in particular the pleasant Mughal gardens. Its also flanked by hills, particularly along its east bank. The Shankaracharya hill provides a very fine view over the lake.

name: Shakhaouath Chondon
review_text:
Dal Lake located at Srinagar and the main attraction of Srinagar, the summer capital of Jammu and Kashmir. The urban lake, which is the second largest in the state, is integral to tourism and recreation in Kashmir and is named the Jewel in the crown of Kashmir.
Shikara (Boat) ride on very popular Dal Lake in Srinagar. Shikara ride is a must do activity for every tourist and is popular the world over, along with the stay in over 1000 House Boats on the lake. Boat passes through Nehru Garden, Floating Market, Village, Vegetable Farms, Lotus Farm, House Boats, and Meena Bazaar. The ride takes at least 2 hours and really very enjoyable. The shore line of the lake, is about 15.5 kilometres (9.6 mi), is encompassed by a boulevard lined with Mughal era gardens, parks, houseboats and hotels. . During the winter season, the temperature sometimes reaches 11 degC (12 degF), freezing the lake

name: Double Click Infomedia
review_text:
Dal is a lake in Srinagar , the summer capital of Jammu and Kashmir. The urban lake, which is the second largest in the state, is integral to tourism and recreation in Kashmir and is named the Jewel in the crown of Kashmir or Srinagars Jewel. The lake is also an important source for commercial operations in fishing and water plant harvesting.
During the winter season, the temperature sometimes reaches 11 degC (12 degF), freezing the lake.
The floating gardens, known as Rad in Kashmiri, blossom with lotus flowers during July and August.
At present, the Dal and its Mughal gardens, Shalimar Bagh and the Nishat Baghon its periphery are undergoing intensive restoration measures to fully address the serious eutrophication problems experienced by the lake.

name: Navdeep Sandhu
review_text:
Dal Lake the best place you can visit in Srinagar. There are Shikara(the small boat) from which you have to travel in the lake. The water is clean and the breeze is breathtaking.There are 1500 plus house boats also nicknamed floating palaces in the lake, built according to British customs. You will have Royal feeling when you enter a houseboat.

The price for the house boat depends on you bargaining ability. All houseboat owners provide Shikara transport to their house guests free of charge. The shikara is also used to provide for other sightseeing locations in the valley, notably a cruise along the Jhelum River, offering scenic views of the Pir Panjal mountains and passing through the famous seven bridges and the backwaters en route.

name: Vishal Mahajan
review_text:
Mesmerizing beauty
SHIKARA BOAT RIDE

12345

font size Print Email

The Dal is famous not only for its beauty, but for its vibrance, because it sustains within its periphery, a life that is unique anywhere in the world. The houseboat and shikara communities have lived for centuries on the Dal, and so complete is their infrastructure on the lake, that they never have to step on land! Doctors, tailors, and bakers - youll see them all in tiny wooden shops on the lake, near picturesque vegetable gardens and acres of lotus gardens.

A shikara ride is one of the most soothing, relaxing aspects of a holiday in Kashmir. Shikaras are long boats which crowd the Srinagar lakes. They are used for getting back and forth from the houseboats or for longer tours. It is worth to take a pleasure ride around the lake in shikara. Shikara is a Gondola type light rowing boat. The two hour boat ride takes tourists on a relaxing sightseeing tour of interior parts of the calm and placid waters of Dal Lake, and be part of shopping- by-shikara expeditions. Because the Dal is so central to the landscape of Srinagar, many places of tourist interest have, over the ages, been built in its vicinity. Nishat and Shalimar gardens as well as Hazratbal mosque are directly accessible by shikara. Mostly crowded, the Shikara boat rides in Kashmir are also used to transport you from land to your houseboat and vice versa. It is worth your time and money to take that joyride ride around the lakes of Kashmir in a shikara. You can also access tourist spots like the Shalimar Garden, Nishat Garden, and the Hazratbal mosque via the Shikara as the Dal Lake is quite central to these places in Srinagar.

While riding on Shikara we can often observe white breasted Kingfishers (Halycon smyrnensis), large striking birds with robust bills perched on the branches of willow trees. These birds concentrate their efforts to hunting on the floating Gardens. These man made islands comprise of reeds, willow rods, aquatic vegetations and and held together with humus consisting of mud from the lake bottom. This is extremely fertile and provide rich source of food in the form of frogs,lizards,mice, grasshoppers and other insects to the Kingfisher.

Sightseeing on a shikara boat in Dal Lake and Nagin lakes culminates to a romantic trip especially if you are seated inside canopies of the Dal lake shikara boats. The feeling of joy and pleasure is unaccountable and the experience definitely unforgettable. The banks of the Dal Lake and Nagin Lake along the Boulevard road in Srinagar, Kashmir feature several Shikara Boat Ghats where the boats are available for hire. There are three main Shikara boat Ghats such as the Dal Gate, Nagin Lake, Hazratbal, Nehru Park, and Gagribal.

name: Anjni Kumar Nandwana
review_text: Dal Lake, Srinagar is popularly known as the Jewel of Srinagar or the Crown of Kashmir. Dal Lake is the second largest lake in Kashmir. This picturesque lake is 26 square km. Spread over a large area, it is the main center of attraction for tourists visiting Srinagar. Situated in the foothills of the Himalayas, this lake is famous for its shikaras i.e. wooden boats and houseboats. A lovely tour of Dal Lake is done by houseboat while a return ride is done by Shikara to Dal Lake and the houseboat. Dal Lake is divided by the causeway into four major basins known as Lokut Dal, Gagriwal, Bod Dal and Nagin. The unmatched natural beauty and natural surroundings of Dal Lake make it the first choice and ideal destination for tourists. Tourists can enjoy the sunrise by sitting on a houseboat or shikara here. Tourists can also come here and enjoy water games which are often organized here. Swimming, water surfing, kayaking, angling and canoeing are the major water sports in Dal Lake.

name: raja Paswan
review_text:
Dal lake is one of major tourist attractions in srinagar. The shikara( boat ride) is costly. We paid Rs.3600 for a boat for 6 people after much negotiations. It was worth or not but definitely a must do thing in srinagar.
The boat is not motorised that is quite good, only man propelled it slowly and slowly.
Sound of paddle in water amidst calmness of valley, and you sipping kahwa is something to feel.
Its not only lake but cumulative effect of surrounding landscapes that make it a worth. Boathouses are all along shore of lake.

Dal lake is economy growing on water. You can get many food items selling on movable boat, even Beer.
They will give you a tour of lake, various shops and a few farms raised on water.

The irony with a tourist place is it doesnt remains the same over the period.
Boathouses, Tourist, Residents dumping garbage in lake destroying its beauty and ecology.
Finally a must take experience in srinagar.

name: Ashwini hajare
review_text: Truly a Jewel of Kashmir, Srinagar; the whole massive expanse of this magnificent lake provides with beauty at every point. Relax in the intricately crafted House Boat, enjoy the shikara ride and shop at the local floating market. Get to know the local culture and history from the shikara guides. You get some of the best sunset and sunrises here. In the winter when the lake freezes you can enjoy ice skating activities. House boats cost around 3000 to 1000 a room depending upon the size and lavishness of the house boat. Shikara ride in off season you can bargain at 150 to 200 inr and in on season it can go Upto 800 to 1000 inr.

review_text: one of the major land mark of Shrinagar, famous for House boats, Shikara & floating Market, the Dal Lake which has the length of 8 Km long and a width of 4 Km, spreads over a total of 26 Sq. Km. The fascinating Dal Lake is divided into two smaller ones the Lokut (small) and Bod (big) Dal. The south western part of the lake has a maximum depth of approximately 12 M. the Dal Lake gets some of its water from spring but is also supplemented by water from the mountain lake, Mar Sar.

review_text: The floating market at Dal Lake is amazing. It opens very early in the morning. From your house boat or hotel, you can take a shikara ride to the floating market. All the vegetables there are fresh, the flowers are fresh and smells beautiful. You can eat local candies called Delicious made of chocolate and walnut. As the name suggests, they are indeed delicious. Feel free to photograph the hustle bustle of the early morning floating market. I had been there a few times during my stay. Its a splendid feeling to be there. Must go there!!

name: Weekend Wanderer Jensen
review_text:
Must visit! I had a wonderful experience boating around the lake. Our guide (the person who manages the boat) was very kind, enthusiastic and informative.
Listen carefully to everything they say and it could lead to wonderful conversations about the local culture and their history.
They usually offer 3 variants in the ride (based on duration and distance), in my opinion, the 2nd variant should do just fine.
Make sure you have your camera/phone charged!
